<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0787 05-01 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0787,0588</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs separate moved on Stoppa, a0735; the Lexcen obituary
moved on some sports circuits.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Ben Lexcen</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben Lexcen, designer of the yacht that
ended the United States' 132-year dominance of the America's Cup
competition, died Sunday after a heart attack. He was 52.
   Lexcen's unique winged-keel design enabled Australia II to
defeat the New York Yacht Club defender Liberty, skippered by
Dennis Conner, and win the cup off Newport, R.I., in 1983.
   The United States won back the America's Cup in 1987 when Conner
skippered Stars & Stripes past defender Kookaburra, which was not
designed by Lexcen.
   Last month, Lexcen unveiled a winged skateboard he predicted
would boost the popularity of that activity.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Henry Hinckley</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDEN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Henry Hinckley, a co-founder of ABC and
an administrator under Presidents Roosevelt and Truman, died
Saturday at age 96.
   Hinckley, an automobile dealer, began his political climb as a
state legislator and mayor of Mount Pleasant.
   During the Depression, he was Utah director and Western regional
director of the Federal Emergency Relief Administration. In 1935,
he was appointed assistant administrator of the Works Progress
Administration.
   Hinckley became chairman of the Civil Aeronautics Authority,
forerunner to the FAA, a year after its creation in 1938. A
promoter of commercial aviation, he was instrumental in the
construction of National Airport in Washington.
   Roosevelt moved him to the Commerce Department in 1940, where he
served as assistant secretary.
   Under Truman he directed the Office of Contract Settlements,
negotiating settlements to defense contracts no longer needed in
peacetime.
   Hinckley took part in the formation of the American Broadcasting
Cos. in 1946, when national television was only a dream. He became
vice president in charge of ABC's Washington, D.C., office,
retiring in 1959. He remained on the board of directors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James McCracken</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metropolitan Opera tenor James McCracken,
acclaimed internationally for his singing of the title role in
Verdi's ``Otello,'' died Friday of complications from a stroke. He
was 61.
   McCracken was believed to have sung ``Otello'' more often than
any tenor in history. His dark-timbered tenor and emotional
intensity were thought by critics to be well suited to the long and
difficult role.
   McCracken was born in Gary, Ind., and served in the Navy. With
the help of the GI Bill, he studied music at Columbia University.
   His opera debut was as Rodolfo in ``La Boheme'' at the Central
City, Colo., Opera in 1952. His Met debut was in a small role in
``La Boheme'' in 1953.
   McCracken leapt into operatic prominence in 1960 when he sang
``Otello'' to great acclaim in Washington, D.C.; Zurich,
Switzerland, and Vienna, Austria.
   He returned to the Met in triumph in 1963, becoming the first
American native to sing ``Otello'' at the hall. In the 1970s he
sang at the Met in ``Aida,'' ``Carmen,'' ``Otello'' twice, ``Le
Prophete'' and ``Tannhauser.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Paolo Stoppa</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paolo Stoppa, one of Italy's foremost stage and
screen character actors, died Sunday at age 81.
   Since 1935, Stoppa appeared in dozens of Italian and
international films. He also founded a theater that employed
director Luchino Visconti early in his career.
   Stoppa played Pope Alexander III in ``Becket.'' Some of his
other film credits include ``Rocco And His Brothers,'' ``Behold A
Pale Horse'' and ``Once Upon A Time In The West.''
</TEXT>
