<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Policeman-Flood     05-01 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Policeman-Flood,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Who Went Home During Flood is Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES PLAINES, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer who abandoned his post
and returned home to help his family during an August flood was
fired Saturday by the Board of Fire and Police Commissioners.
   The three-member panel earlier had found Patrolman Clifford
Launius guilty of eight of nine charges of misconduct.
   Joseph Kozenczak, the chief of police in this northwest Chicago
suburb, sought the dismissal shortly after Launius left his post
without permission. Launius said he feared for the safety of his
family when nine inches of rain hit the area, causing severe
flooding.
   The 3-0 vote came at the end of a nearly three-hour meeting,
said commissioner Herman Herzog.
   ``No decision is easy when you have to remove a man from his
job,'' he said.
   The decision to fire Launius went into effect immediately, but
Launius could appeal in Circuit Court, Herzog said.
   Launius said following the vote that he had no regrets.
   ``I felt that my family was in danger,'' he said. ``I hope to
God I never have to make that kind of decision. ... It wasn't
easy,'' Launius said, adding that he plans to appeal.
   Launius had been suspended without pay since late summer.
</TEXT>
