<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 0203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SubAground 2ndLd-Writethru a0664 05-01 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sub Aground, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0664,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Submarine Runs Aground, Freed By Tugs, Tide</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf of 1st Add with arrival of sub at Bangor, no
explanation of need for towing.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aging Navy nuclear-powered attack
submarine was freed largely unscathed early Saturday after going
aground in sand and gravel off Fox Island in south Puget Sound,
Navy officials said.
   ``There was no internal damage and the hull was not damaged,''
said Petty Officer 2nd Class Mike Kriesel, following an initial
investigation.
   The USS Sam Houston was moored to a Navy barge in Carr Inlet,
about one-half mile from where it went aground south of Tacoma, for
about half a day of further checks by divers and other personnel.
   ``The only damage they found was to some external equipment that
was put on the ship for sound testing,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Kathy
Woodcock at the Trident nuclear submarine base at Bangor.
   The sub, which was pulled free by four Navy tugs on a rising
tide at 4:18 a.m. Saturday, was towed to Bangor late Saturday
night, she said. She added that she did not know why it was towed,
rather than moving under its own power, and would not have further
word on the vessel before Monday.
   The Ethan Allen-class sub, based at Pearl Harbor, was grounded
around 6 p.m. Friday on Carr Inlet about 100 yards off the
southeast end of Fox Island, with the tide going out, said Navy
spokesman Fred Watson at the Bangor base.
   No one was injured, and the sub's 142 crew members remained
aboard.
   ``She wasn't that far dug in,'' Watson said of the stuck sub. As
an attack sub, said Watson, the vessel carried no missiles.
   A small crowd of residents and reporters gathered on the beach
of the residential island south of Tacoma to look at the sub Friday
night.
   ``I looked down the beach and saw this nuclear-powered whale
beached,'' said Dr. John West, a Fox Island resident.
   A sonar pod beneath the sub was visible as the tide went out,
and ``the water was way underneath the water line,'' said Steve
Collins, 41, a resident of the island. ``It's an amazing sight.''
   The tugs were assisted by the submarine rescue ship USS
Florikan. The 410-foot-long Sam Houston sustained minor damage to
exterior hull equipment and will undergo repairs at Bangor before
continuing operations, Watson said.
   The Navy would not disclose how the ship grounded; Watson said
an investigation was under way. The sub was commanded by Cmdr.
Phillip J. Kuehlen, who was not immediately available for comment,
Watson said.
   The sub was in Carr Inlet, where the water is about 350 feet
deep, for testing to determine how quiet it is in the water, Watson
said. The Navy regularly tests submarine acoustics in the area.
   About 15 minutes before the grounding, West said he noticed ``a
lot of smoke from the sub, and they dove under the water,
presumably on a routine measure.'' About 15 minutes later, Navy men
in T-shirts rushed to the beach, and West said he then saw the sub
was grounded.
   Jim Saathoff, another island resident, said he had seen the
submarine moving ``at a pretty good clip'' beneath the water with
its scope up and then, ``for whatever reason, it turned toward the
beach.''
   The bow of the sub was completely exposed where it ran aground
on a gradually sloping, sandy beach, said Saathoff.
   The Sam Houston was launched in February 1961 at Newport News,
Va., and commissioned 13 months later.
   Watson said the 250-foot Florikan, specially equipped for
assisting submarines in trouble, happened to be in Puget Sound for
crew rest and relaxation and recalibration of instruments. Like the
Sam Houston, the Florikan's home port is Pearl Harbor.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>The Ethan, 5th graf.</HEAD>
