<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Soviet-MayDay     05-01 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet-May Day,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Ambassadors End Boycott of May Day Celebrations in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western ambassadors attended May Day celebrations
in Moscow Sunday for the first time since the 1979 Soviet drive
into Afghanistan and saw a parade strikingly free of the strident
anti-American rhetoric of the past.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev led 11 other Politburo
members onto the masoleum where the body of Soviet founder Vladimir
I. Lenin lies to view the festivities marking the workers holiday,
one of the most important dates in the Soviet calendar.
   For two hours, Muscovites carrying banners and towing floats
extolling ``perestroika'' (reconstruction) ``glasnost'' (openness),
worldwide nuclear disarmament and other Communist Party programs
strolled past the massed Kremlin leadership and across sun-dappled
Red Square.
   One float demanded ``freedom for the people of South Africa,''
but few dealt with international affairs in detail, beyond calling
for peace and disarmament.
   One large float stressed the need for good superpower relations,
depicting a handshake against the background of the U.S. and Soviet
flags with the inscription ``Da!''
   During the kickoff of the parade, Gorbachev had an animated
conversation with party ideologue Yegor K. Ligachev, the No. 2
Kremlin leader who some reports say recently had a falling-out with
Gorbachev.
   U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock made the first appearance by an
American ambassador at May Day since 1980, when the United States
began boycotting the ceremony to protest the Kremlin's armed
intervention in Afghanistan.
   ``I'm here first of all since this is not a military-related
holiday and because the agreements have been signed in Geneva,'
said Matlock, referring to accords signed in the Swiss city last
month that mandate a pullout of the 115,000 Soviet troops from
Afghanistan beginning May 15.
   ``Our president is due in less than a month, and it seems to me
that one should resume normal attendance at non-military events,''
the U.S. ambassador added.
   President Ronald Reagan is due in Moscow on May 29-June 2 for
his fourth summit meeting with Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev's wife Raisa, dressed in a long black coat cinched at
the waist and a purple silk scarf fastened with a brooch, told
reporters she was looking forward to the chance to host the Reagans
in Moscow.
   ``We await a new meeting and new acquaintances,'' Mrs. Gorbachev
said, smiling and clasping a bouquet of red carnations wrapped in
plastic.
   Also attending were the West German ambassador, Andreas
Meyer-Landrut, British ambassador Sir Bryan Cartledge, French
ambassador Yves Pagniez, Italian ambassador Sergio Romano and other
top West European envoys.
   The West German ambassador, Andreas Meyer-Landrut said it was
the first time ambassadors from all European Economic Community
countries attended May Day festivities in Moscow since the Soviets
sent tanks and troops into Afghanistan in December 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
