<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Netherlands-Blast 4thLd-Writethru   05-01 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Netherlands-Blast, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0687,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three British Soldiers Slain, IRA Claims Responsibility</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with IRA claiming responsibility,
ID of one victim, ADDS quotes and details. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NIEUWBERGEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three British servicemen were
killed and three injured in separate car bomb and shooting
incidents Sunday near the West German border. The Irish Republican
Army claimed responsibility.
   All the servicemen had come from West Germany, where they were
based, to the Netherlands for Saturday festivities surrounding the
official 50th birthday celebration of Queen Beatrix.
   A British Ministry of Defense spokesman who spoke on condition
of anonymity reported the attacks but refused comment on reports
that terrorists were to blame.
   ``We're not saying anything along those lines. ... We're waiting
for the results of investigations by Dutch police and military
authorities,'' he said.
   The IRA, which is fighting to oust Great Britain from Northern
Ireland, claimed responsibility in a coded message to Belfast media.
   It was the first reported attack on Great Britain in the
Netherlands in almost a decade. In 1979, British Ambassador Richard
Sykes was shot to death outside his Hague residence, and the IRA
claimed responsibility.
   In the first incident Sunday, in the southern city of Roermond,
one serviceman was killed and two injured when gunmen fired on
their car at about 1 a.m., officials said.
   Thirty minutes later, in the village of Nieuwbergen, 30 miles to
the north, two servicemen were killed instantly and one was
seriously injured when their British-licensed car exploded as they
were getting into it on the country town's main street, according
to police spokesman Louis Steens.
   ``I heard the bang and ran there straightaway,'' said a man who
was sitting in a nearby cafe.
   ``The car was already on fire. Twenty meters (67 feet) away, a
boy was lying all covered in blood,'' said the bystander, who
refused to give his name.
   ``The bodies were in such condition that they could not
immediately be identified,'' Steens told The Associated Press.
   He said the Dutch Army bomb squad searched the wreckage and the
area for traces of exposives. Another British-licensed car parked
in front of the nearby Bacchus discotheque, where police believe
the three soldiers spent the evening, was also searched, but police
found nothing.
   The Bacchus is heavily frequented by British military personnel,
according to local residents.
   After the explosion, 60 houses in the town were evacuated as a
safety precaution.
   The Ministry of Defense spokesman said the servicemen involved
in the Roermond shooting were based at a Royal Air Force base in
Wildenrath in West Germany.
   The dead man was identified as Senior Aircraftsman Ian Shinner,
20, of Winsford in Cheshire. The two injured men were in a nearby
Dutch hospital and were not immediately identified.
   The Dutch National News Agency reported that their car was
riddled with bullet holes.
   There was no information immediately available on the identities
of the Nieuwbergen blast victims. But TV-AM, Britain's commercial
breakfast television program, said they were from the RAF Laarbruch
base in West Germany, close to Wildenrath.
   Several British military installations are along the Dutch-West
German border, which runs only a few miles east of Nieuwbergen.
   The British command in West Germany issued an alert for all
British military personnel living in The Netherlands or near the
Dutch-West German border, or planning to travel through the
Netherlands.
   The British command ordered the military personnel to check
their cars for explosive devices, according to the British
Broadcasting Corporation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
