<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 1131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Italian-POWs     05-01 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italian-POWs,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Prisoners Return To Panhandle POW Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEREFORD, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Italians who were prisoners of
war in Texas have returned to embrace as friends the people they
once considered their enemy.
   More than 100 residents of Deaf Smith and Castro counties
welcomed the 16 former prisoners and their wives who returned for a
visit Saturday to the World War II prisoner of war camp near this
Panhandle community.
   ``It is good to see the same place and remember the years I
lost,'' said Angelo Sacchi, who was 20 when he was captured. ``I
have mostly good memories, particularly with the American nurses,
because I was hospitalized for three months.''
   They visited a chapel they built in 1945 as a monument to five
countrymen who died while at the camp 50 miles southwest of
Amarillo.
   Auelio Manzoni, a former Italian officer, said the prisoners
were glad to come to Texas because prison life here was better than
in France or England.
   ``It is a good thing to remember what was our life for three
years,'' Manzoni said. ``But it was still the life of a prisoner.''
   Clara Vick, a member of Castro County Historical Society, gave
the former POWs a scrap book of newspaper clippings and documents
related to the camp. She also gave each former prisoner a piece of
the camp's barbed wire fence.
   The visitors donated $100 to the Castro County Historical
Commission for restoration of their chapel.
   ``One of the greatest compliments these men have paid us is the
fact that they have returned to visit,'' said the Rev. James Salvi,
who worked at the POW camp during 1943-49.
   The visitors planned to stay in the Panhandle until Monday.
</TEXT>
