<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EthiopianStowaways     05-01 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopian Stowaways,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Ethiopian Boys Who Stowed Away On Cargo Ship Apply For Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Ethiopian teen-agers reached
Florida after hiding in a cargo ship for two weeks as stowaways and
immediately applied for political asylum.
   ``We're afraid of the wars,'' 14-year-old Mahari Gebremskel said
through an interpreter. He was referring to rebellions that have
been under way for years in two northern provinces against
Ethiopia's Marxist government.
   The boys, ranging in age from 12 to 15, had been hiding among
27,000 130-pound bags of coffee aboard the freighter Galveston Bay.
   David Angotti of the Jacksonville office of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service took the unusual step of releasing the boys
Saturday to the temporary custody of Jacksonville residents,
including several Ethiopian couples.
   ``The only reason they're being allowed off the ship is their
age,'' Angotti said, adding that it's unusual for the INS to
receive requests for political asylum from stowaways who are
children.
   ``They want to build a new life,'' said Linda Bellamy , a
volunteer refugee worker for St. Phillips Episcopal Church who
helped find homes for the youths. ``They were brave. In order for
them to come this far there had to be a reason.''
   Steven P. Kapustka , operations manager for Eller & Co., agent
for the Galveston Bay, said he learned the stowaways were on board
last week.
   He said an INS official boarded the Galveston Bay, owned by
Afram Lines of Tampa, on Friday and interviewed the youngsters
while the vessel was anchored off the coast waiting to enter the
St. Johns River channel.
   Jacksonville was the Galveston Bay's first port since leaving
Ethiopia about April 17, Kapustka said.
</TEXT>
