<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BunnyReunion     05-01 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bunny Reunion,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Playboy Bunnies Hold Charity Bash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of former Playboy bunnies have showed
they can still throw a good party and aren't slowed down by having
to dye gray hairs and leave their college-age children at home.
   ``They've only gotten prettier,'' said Patty Mennen, 42, who
wore the fluffy tail and tall ears, the costume that was worn from
1965 through 1970 at clubs in Miami and New York.
   For many of the more than 100 who attended the reunion Saturday,
it was the first time they'd seen each other in decades.
   ``You haven't changed a bit,'' squealed Gloria Hendry, a bunny
from 1964 to 1973, when she spotted Ms. Mennen.
   Many of the women are no longer struggling as they were when
they were younger and earning a living by entertaining in their
skin-tight outfits.
   Ms. Hendry, an actress who appeared in a James Bond movie, said
that being a bunny taught her ``how to be a hostess with the
mostest. It taught me how to talk to people.''
   Mona Lisa, 25, a singer, worked in the Empire Playboy Club, part
of an attempt to revive the chain of clubs. It closed in June 1986
after just eight months.
   ``The memory will live on forever,'' she said. ``Times change,
people expect different things.''
   Ms. Mennen, who wore white bunny ears Saturday, remembered
people picketing the old New York club, which closed in 1982.
   ``They said, `How do you do this?' I said, `I'm laughing all the
way to the bank,''' she recalled.
   One of the most popular people at the party was Betty Dozier
Tate of Queens, a seamstress who made bunny outfits beginning in
1961.
   ``These are my kids,'' she said. ``I wish Hugh Hefner had
another nightclub.''
   But Ms. Mennen commented: ``It was just a fad.''
   The reunion was organized by former bunny Anna Lederer, 37, who
left her native Trinidad at 17, earned a degree in international
relations at the University of Geneva and later opened an import
business.
   Mrs. Lederer, who worked from 1968 to 1971 in the old Manhattan
club, arranged the reunion at the suggestion of her 13-year-old son.
   Ms. magazine founder Gloria Steinem, who once took a job as a
bunny to write an expose, said she rejected an invitation to attend
the reunion.
   ``When we have a dinner where former bunnies feel able to tell
the truth, it will make a lot more money. And then I'll come,'' she
said.
   Money raised by the $80 fee for bunnies and their dates and the
$200 for others will benefit Cancer Care Inc.
</TEXT>
