<HEAD>Five Killed, 23 Hurt In Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people were killed and 23 were
injured in ethnic violence in a working class neighborhood of this
port city, reports said Sunday.
   The official English language daily, the Pakistan Times, said
three people died Sunday. Karachi's Dawn newspaper said two other
people died late Saturday from injuries sustained in the violence.
   Officials were unavailable for comment, and government offices
were closed in observance of the May 1 holiday.
   The trouble started Friday night when a traffic accident in
western Karachi led to rioting and gunfire between Pathan youths,
who trace their roots to northern Pakistan, and Mohajirs, who
immigrated from India.
   Karachi, Pakistan's largest city with a population of 7 million,
has been a hotbed of ethnic violence in recent years.
   Hundreds were killed in November and December 1986 when Pathans
and Mohajirs battled in the streets of several neighborhoods.
