<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan-RailStrike     05-01 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Rail Strike,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Halts Rail Service For First Time In 101 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rail service throughout Taiwan was halted
for the first time in 101 years Sunday when train drivers staged a
one-day strike to press demands for higher wages.
   ``It never happened before in the railway history here. Our
trains even ran during World War II,'' said Chou Chin-sung,
director of the main Taipei railroad station.
   Loudspeakers at the station broadcast apologies to stranded
passengers and urged them to collect refunds on their tickets and
take buses.
   Chou estimated the strike would cost the Taiwan Railway
Administration, which runs most of this island's passenger and
freight services, $1.2 million.
   The trains carry roughly 360,000 passengers on a regular Sunday.
   The Train Drivers Club, which represents 1,500 workers, called
the strike to coincide with the May Day labor holiday. It told
drivers to return to work Monday.
   The drivers work 12 hours a day and earn an average monthly
salary of $700. They want a 10 percent increase.
   The rail administration has offered to increase salaries 4
percent to 8 percent.
   Chang Shou-tsen, director of the railway administration, told
reporters the administration would meet with the strikers to try to
negotiate a settlement.
</TEXT>
