<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Economy     05-01 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Economy,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia Goes on a Shopping Spree in Economic Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavs are entering the final
days of a national shopping binge spurred by fears of huge price
increases when a government freeze ends next month.
   ``The country looks like it is preparing for war,'' said one
shopper last week in a crowded Belgrade supermarket. ``Everybody is
piling up stocks of staples at home.''
   Dragan Petrovic, a manager of a downtown Belgrade supermarket,
said he now sells one ton of sugar, half a ton of coffee and 15,000
bottles of cooking oil every day, which equals normal sales for a
month.
   ``If this shopping spree continues, they will even buy my
counter,'' Petrovic said.
   The middle of May is shaping up as a crucial juncture in
communist Yugoslavia's post-World War II history. The government is
facing a confidence vote, trying to lock up new credits abroad, and
introducing unpopular economic measures at home.
   Vice Premier Janez Zemljaric said recently that Yugoslavia
``faces economic collapse'' unless foreign creditors grant a
financial reprieve.
   Living standards of Yugoslavs have already slipped to mid-1960
levels since 1980, resulting in an unprecedented 150,000 strikes
last year.
   Local media have reported that about 80 percent of the country's
manufacturers have prepared new prices for May 15, when the
government lifts the price freeze. New prices are expected to be 50
percent to 70 percent above current levels.
   The government of Premier Branko Mikulic said it has prepared a
new economic program aimed at defusing the expected price and
inflation explosion.
   However, doubting improvement under Mikulic, the parliament of
Slovenia, the country's most developed region, has started a formal
procedure to unseat the federal government.
   It's the first such move in communist Yugoslavia and is to be
voted on later this month by the nation's five other republics.
   Slovenian officials have bitterly criticized Mikulic and his
administration for failing to curb the 170 percent inflation and
for intervening in the economy.
   Government officials counter that their new program includes
market-oriented measures, expected eventually to curb prices, and
much less state intervention.
   The officials said the new measures were worked out with the
International Monetary Fund, with which Yugoslavia recently reached
a draft one-year agreement expected to be approved May 13. The
program aims to reduce inflation to 95 percent annually by the end
of this year.
   A precondition for the new program are fresh loans and
rescheduling of a large part of the country's $20 billion debt,
government officials said.
   Yugoslavia's creditors, mainly 16 Western governments and
leading commercial banks, have told the country that new Monetary
Fund credit would be a precondition for a fresh refinancing deal
over several years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
