<DOCNO> AP880501-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 1142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BaseClosings Bjt   05-01 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Base Closings, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress May Close Some Unneeded Military Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searching for new ways to cut federal
spending, Congress may finally be ready to butcher one of its most
sacred cows _ outdated and unneeded military bases.
   ``We no longer need to guard the Pony Express routes to the Wild
West. We no longer need to maintain moated forts to guard against
assault by British sailing ships,'' said Sen. William Roth, R-Del.
   ``We all know why these unnecessary bases have been kept open,''
Roth said. ``They have been maintained for selfish political
reasons in order to maintain a flow of defense dollars into our
states. But the budgetary good times are gone. We simply cannot
justify throwing money away.''
   Roth is the chief sponsor of a measure approved last week by the
Senate Armed Services Committee as an amendment to next year's
Pentagon budget bill.
   Roth's proposal would create a nine-member commission, appointed
by the secretary of defense, to look at bases around the country
and recommend, solely on the basis of national security needs,
which ones should be kept open. The secretary would then be free to
implement those recommendations, unless specifically reversed by
Congress.
   The same plan has been introduced in the House by Rep. Richard
K. Armey, R-Texas.
   Both Roth and Armey cite various estimates from previous studies
that closing unneeded bases could save between $2 billion and $5
billion a year.
   Bases mean jobs, and legislators have been loath to see payrolls
cut. In the decades after World War II, the Pentagon was generally
allowed to do as it pleased on the issue, with the exception of a
handful of bases protected by key members of Congress. Between 1961
and 1977, the Defense Department cut or closed 3,600 installations
and saved an estimated $5 billion a year.
   But in 1975, the Air Force proposed shutting down Loring Air
Force Base, a B-52 base in northern Maine that the service said was
unneeded. Maine's congressional delegation succeeded in winning
congressional approval for a new law that required costly _ up to
$1 million each _ environmental studies for any Pentagon attempt to
close a base.
   The studies were also lengthy and gave critics opposed to
shutting a base plenty of ammunition. But requirements for the
studies would be waived under the pending commission proposal.
   Since 1975, no major military installations have been closed. In
1979, the Pentagon proposed mothballing 157 facilities and laying
off 45,000 personnel, but dropped it in the face of congressional
opposition.
   Six years later, Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger suggested
22 installations he said could be shut down, but Congress reacted
strongly again and the idea went nowhere.
   Politics cuts both ways, Armey noted. Last year, Republican
congressman said 28 bases could be closed, but 27 of them were in
districts represented in the House by Democrats. In 1986,
Weinberger said three more facilities could be closed, but they
were all in the districts of Democrats critical of Weinberger and
his idea was never seriously considered.
   Last year, Armey lost, 199-192, when he tried to put his base
closure amendment into the Pentagon budget bill.
   But the atmosphere is different this year, partly because of
congressional agreement that the military budget is one of the few
places left to look in the effort to find spending cuts. His plan
now has 112 co-sponsors.
   The chairman of the Senate and House Armed Services committees
suggest that this year's opportunity to close bases is a unique one.
   ``This is probably an area of waste and inefficiency that can be
seized this year, unlike any other year,'' Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
said.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., agreed. ``There's a good chance this
year because of a variety of circumstances,'' he said. But ``even
though we've got a lot of people on board on this, there's still a
lot of opposition,'' he added.
   Under the commission plan, the panel would have to make its
recommendations by next Dec. 31 and Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci, who supports the idea, would have 15 days to accept or
reject the entire list. That decision would be made only five days
before the Reagan administration leaves office.
   ``You've got a secretary of defense who's willing to make a
choice as he leaves office,'' Aspin said. ``That's a big factor.''
   Armey's plan is not part of the Pentagon budget bill now on the
House floor, but it will be considered separately by the chamber
within the next month, Aspin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
