<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NavalHospital     05-01 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Naval Hospital,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Naval Hospital Has Survived Several Closing Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Base Closings Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philadelphia Naval Hospital frequently
appears on the Pentagon's chopping block, but it has escaped the ax
so far.
   The death blow has been postponed at least until completion of
two military studies of medical care in the region.
   In February 1987, then-Secretary of the Navy John F. Lehman Jr.
proposed shutting the hospital within eight months and relocating
patients to Walson Army Medical Center at Fort Dix, N.J.
   When Philadelphia-area lawmakers objected, Lehman modified the
plan to allow patients to be treated at a Philadelphia-area
hospital or medical group to be chosen through competitive bidding.
But the hospital was still scheduled to close by Sept. 30.
   However, the hospital did not close, and on Oct. 6, Lehman's
successor, James H. Webb Jr., told a House subcommittee the
shutdown was on hold pending completion of the studies.
   The hospital also survived two earlier closing attempts.
   In February 1986, Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger
included the hospital in a list of three installations he said were
unneeded and could be closed to save money. But opposition from
area lawmakers saved it.
   In 1980, the hospital was also in danger of closing. But it
survived then because of the arrival of the aircraft carrier
Saratoga for overhaul at the nearby Philadelphia Naval Shipyard.
   The hospital was built in 1935 and had a daily patient load of
1,000 during the Vietnam War.
   It employed about 820 people in 1986, but just 400 a year later
when Lehman proposed its elimination. By February 1987, its daily
patient load was just 50.
</TEXT>
