<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Lowry     05-01 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lowry,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colorado Politicians Fought Off Move To Close Lowry Air Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Base Closings Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When then-Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger
proposed closing Lowry Air Force Base two years ago, Colorado
politicians and business leaders banded together to thwart the
effort.
   The base was one of three military installations that Weinberger
suggested should be closed in a test of Congress' willingness to
save money.
   The Lowry center, with an annual payroll of $187 million,
originally was an Army Air Corps base used during World War II to
train B-29 bomber crews. It now employs 4,350 military personnel
and 2,900 civilians and provides training in avionics, munitions
and intelligence to about 3,900 students.
   Real estate developers were excited at the prospect of such
prime real estate as Lowry, surrounded by residential areas and
businesses, being opened for development. They said the property
was worth $170 million.
   But Denver-area business and government leaders said the plan
would pull $867 million from the economy.
   In a rare show of bipartisan action, Rep. Patricia Schroeder,
D-Colo., and Sen. William Armstrong, R-Colo., fired off letters to
Weinberger demanding further explanation.
   Other Colorado congressmen asked for an investigation by the
House Armed Services Committee, and then-Sen. Gary Hart, D-Colo.,
accused Weinberger of playing politics by singling out bases for
closure in the districts of outspoken defense critics, such as
Schroeder.
   In January 1987, the Pentagon sent a three-paragraph letter to
the Senate Armed Services Committee saying Lowry would remain open.
</TEXT>
