<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Loring     05-01 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Loring,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Existence of Maine Air Base Threatened Many Times</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Base Closings Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMESTONE, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loring Air Force Base may be tucked away
in the northern Maine woods, but its existence has not been hidden
from officials in Washington, who have slashed costs and tried to
close the facility many times.
   The Strategic Air Command Base was hit by several reductions
during the early 1970s. Presidents Ford and Carter tried to phase
out the base in the late '70s because of fears its proximity to the
Atlantic would make it vulnerable to submarine-launched ballistic
missiles.
   But the Pentagon backed down after Maine's congressional
delegation and a ``Save Loring Committee'' successfully argued that
poor, rural Aroostook County would be economically devastated by
the loss of the base.
   Since then, the military has spent about $150 million to
renovate the 2,000-acre base, prompting Rep. Olympia Snowe,
R-Maine, to say in 1984 that that spending indicated the Air
Force's ``long-range intentions toward Loring.''
   And in recent years, the base has been called valuable for its
strategic location to Canada and because it is the closest Air
Force base in the continental United States to the Soviet Union.
   Loring was carved out of a virgin forest hard by the New
Brunswick, Canada, border following World War II. It currently
employs 3,760 military and 564 civilian personnel and assigns its
pilots to fly B-52 bombers and KC-135 jets.
</TEXT>
