<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MOVEFindings Bjt   05-01 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MOVE Findings, Bjt,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Releasing Report Three Years After Fatal MOVE Siege</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY6, PX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury will release its findings on
criminal intent this week in the police bombing three years ago of
the radical group MOVE in which 11 people died and 61 homes were
destroyed by a resulting fire.
   Police arranged the bombing of the barricaded and heavily
fortified row house on May 13, 1985, in an attempt only to evict
the MOVE followers. Neighbors had complained to city officials and
threatened to take matters into their own hands if nothing was done
about the group.
   Members of the mysterious group, whose name did not stand for
anything in particular, championed back-to-nature rituals, lived in
filth, refused to send their children to school, and openly
disobeyed health and safety laws, authorities said.
   An investigating commission said the group ``had evolved into an
authoritarian, violence-threatening cult.''
   The police bomb touched off a rooftop fire that soon raged out
of control while firemen held back, afraid they would be hit by
gunfire that had echoed through the neighborhood. The 11 killed,
five of them children, were all inside the MOVE house.
   No one has been accused of any criminal act in the bombing. But
both Philadelphia County and federal grand juries began
investigating. The Philadelphia report is due Tuesday.
   ``I would really be hard-pressed, quite frankly, to see how any
grand jury could come out with any indictments other than a
scathing report,'' said Robert Hurst, president of the Fraternal
Order of Police.
   Officers built the bomb and dropped it from a helicopter after
getting approval from Mayor W. Wilson Goode.
   A special commission appointed by Goode later charged the mayor
was ``grossly negligent'' in approving the bombing. It also
condemned the use of gunfire by police as ``reckless'' and
``unconscionable.''
   Relatives of the mostly black MOVE victims denounced Goode, the
first black mayor in the nation's fifth largest city, as ``a
murderer'' and have sued the city for damages.
   Only two people, a woman and boy, escaped from the house. The
12-year-old boy claimed others tried to flee but were driven back
by gunfire.
   Sources quoted in Saturday's editions of The Philadelphia
Inquirer and Philadelphia Daily News said the grand jury would
recommend no criminal charges but would be harshly critical of
officials involved.
   ``The charges wouldn't survive a preliminary hearing,'' said an
unidentified source quoted by the Daily News, which said sources
told it the panel concluded that proving criminal intent would be
difficult.
   ``It's a very detailed legal analysis of everything that
happened on that day,'' a source who spoke on condition of
anonymity told the Inquirer. ``This will lay out in one complete
document by a grand jury the facts as they found them to be and, I
think, will lay rest to virtually every question that exists.''
   District Attorney Ronald Castille, asked about his nearly
two-year investigation of the case, refused to say whether he
expected criminal indictments. ``It's totally up to the grand
jury,'' he said.
   ``No comment,'' echoed Joseph Kovitsky of the Justice
Department, whose attorneys are in charge of an investigation into
whether the bombing violated anyone's civil rights.
   The federal grand jury also is reportedly winding up its work.
   Goode, who took responsibility for approving the dropping of the
bomb, has said repeatedly that he doesn't believe he will be
indicted.
   Other possible targets are former city Managing Director Leo
Brooks, who ran operations at the MOVE scene, former Police
Commissioner Gregore Sambor, who planned the bombing, and Fire
Commissioner William Richmond.
   Damage caused by the police action has exceeded $20 million,
including rebuilding the burned-down neighborhood that originally
left some 250 homeless.
   The mayor barely won re-election last November, winning by only
17,000 votes out of morethan 750,000 cast in a city where Democrats
have a nearly 3 to 1 edge.
   Surviving MOVE members have disappeared or are in jail. Founder
John Africa, born as Vincent Leaphart, died in the fire.
   Children once a central part of the group have been cared for
and raised by the city, to the extent of private tutoring, in an
effort to return them to society.
</TEXT>
