<DOCNO> AP880501-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 1224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-VP Bjt   05-01 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-VP, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Stays Mum on Vice Presidential Pick But Speculation Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush says there ``isn't a short list,
there isn't a long list'' yet of possible running mates, but he
indicates with some understatement that he wants to use less frenzy
in the selection than Ronald Reagan did eight years ago.
   ``I hope I'll make as good a choice but I'll use a different
method,'' says the vice president, who clinched enough delegates
last week to put a lock on the Republican presidential nomination.
   Bush was an 11th hour compromise at the 1980 convention after a
chaotic few days during which Reagan toyed with the idea of sharing
the ticket with former President Gerald Ford.
   With the luxury of time, Bush insists he hasn't begun to even
consider a vice presidential choice or to set up a selection
process _ and likely won't pick a running mate until after the
Democratic convention in July.
   ``The only list of names is the one he's got in his mind and he
isn't telling anybody,'' spokesman Peter Teeley said.
   But that doesn't stop the speculation from flying.
   As Bush travels around the country, he is constantly bombarded
with questions on the subject. More often than not, the queries
have a clear regional flavor.
   Campaigning in Buffalo, Bush was asked if he might pick
vanquished rival Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y. In Hershey, Pa., reporters
wanted to know about former Pennsylvania Gov. Richard Thornburgh.
In Philadelphia, it was New Jersey Governor Tom Kean; In
Evansville, Ind., Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind.
   ``I really have not sat down with advisers or set out the
procedures to follow,'' Bush told reporters last week. ``Of course,
I'm going to do that.''
   Conventional political wisdom suggests that the nominee can do
best by selecting a running mate from a different region of the
country from his own.
   For Bush, that would rule out a lot of potential contenders
since he claims links to Texas, where he maintains a voting
residence; Maine, where he has a home; Connecticut, where he grew
up; and Massachusetts, where he was born.
   That appears to leave the West and Midwest. And among those
frequently mentioned as possibilities are California Gov. George
Deukmejian, Illinois Governor Jim Thompson or one of the Doles,
either former rival Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas or his wife, Elizabeth.
   But Bush downplays geography as a crucial factor.
   ``We are in a new communications age. These geographical things
are important but far less important than they used to be,'' he
suggested recently.
   The vice president has denied reports that he had already set up
a search team, claiming ``no one authorized by me'' is involved in
any such activity.
   Bush aides say he will exercise more caution in picking a ticket
mate because, as vice president himself for eight years, he is
extremely sensitive to the nature of the job.
   Bush says he wants to make sure he picks someone who's on the
same wave length as he is, as well as a person _ he is careful to
say ``man or woman'' _ qualified to take over as president should
anything happen to him.
   Along with Elizabeth Dole, three other women are mentioned
prominently in speculation as possible running mates: former U.N.
ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick, Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor and Kansas Sen. Nancy Landon Kassebaum.
   But Bush just isn't giving out any hints, one way or the other.
   ``I vowed not to get into speculation on that question until
after the Democratic convention and then probably not say anything
about it,'' he said.
   Agreeing there isn't much excitement on the Republican side of
the presidential race these days, Bush also hints that withholding
the name will provide an ``element of suspense'' that might pass as
excitement.
   Still, Bush says suggestions keep coming to him unsolicited
``over the transom, under the door, in plain brown envelopes.''
   At one news conference, he told reporters that he had, in fact,
just received one, patting his shirt pocket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
