<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 1258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Reporter'sNotebook     05-01 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Reporter's Notebook,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Picks Up Endorsement From Beyond the Grave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When George Bush visited Ohio State
University, he picked up one legendary Buckeye's endorsement from
beyond the grave.
   The vice president got a spirited reception at the Student Union
over the weekend after a rousing introduction from Gene Watts, an
Ohio State history professor who is a Republican state senator.
   Watts doubled as a medium on this occasion, too, delivering up
this message for Bush from the late, great Ohio State football
coach, Woody Hayes.
   ``Woody and I would often get together, not to discuss football,
but rather history and politics,'' Watts said.
   ``In one of those conversations _ and I'm remembering this I
believe exactly _ Woody Hayes, who was just a strong supporter of
George Bush, said to me, `Professor, George Bush is going to be the
best president in the 20th century,''' Watts said to cheers.
   Bush and Hayes were buddies. The vice president attended the
funeral of the colorful, irascible coach who lost his job after
striking an opposing team's player.
   Bush picked up the football metaphor and ran with it.
   ``This is the age of glamour and hot rhetoric, but look at
Woody's record: 13 Big Ten titles, eight Rose Bowls, two national
championships. ... It's exactly what we're going to do: We're going
to pound out those yards, 3 yards and a cloud of dust, and whip
either (Jesse) Jackson or (Michael) Dukakis. Let me at 'em come
fall!''
   His rivals, he said, are full of ``gloom and doom. They want to
drop back, fall on the ball and then punt.''
   Bush went from metaphor to reality, donning a scarlet athletic
jacket and walking to midfield before 60,000 Ohio State fans to
give the referees the official game ball for a spring football
scrimmage.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush often talks about how happy he is to have sewed up the
Republican nomination, and how eager to get on with the fall
campaign.
   But the race he really seems to want to run has already been
waged, eight years ago.
   He seldom fails to invoke the memory of a Democratic shade,
Jimmy Carter, who lost the White House to Ronald Reagan and Bush in
1980.
   The memory of Carter ``hangs over Democrats like a shadow, an
unwanted reminder of the last time they were in Washington,'' Bush
said at a Cleveland rally.
   In Columbus, he said the Democrats' rhetoric ``sounds exactly
like Jimmy Carter _ prime rate of interest at 21{ percent and
double-digit inflation, and blaming the American people for
failure. ... It is an exact overlay of what went on from 1977 to
1981.''
   Bush lauds ``the longest recovery in history'' that has occurred
on Reagan's watch _ 64 months long, with 15 million new jobs.
   He seldom mentions the near tripling of the national debt that
has also occurred on his watch. He calls the deficit the biggest
economic problem, but says, ``I blame the Congress. They are
spending us into debt.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush's syntax sometimes gets the best of him, and he coins words
with abandon.
   A paean to the American spirit _ ``the spirit of optimism and
determination that enabled American settlers to push past the snows
and the deserts of the West,'' as he said in Marietta, Ohio _ came
out this way in a Fort Wayne, Ind., factory: ``We're the United
States of America. We rolled back the frontiers and battled the
deserts and the snows.''
   Elsewhere in Fort Wayne, drug traffickers became
``narco-trafficanters.''
   He complained to reporters in Cleveland about the glamorizing of
drugs in a video that he and his wife rented. Bush said the movie,
which he did not name, was ``almost a societal condone-ation of
cocaine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
