<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UncommonMen     05-01 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uncommon Men,0757</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men At All-Women College Say It Isn't Such Fun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH HADLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Johnson's friends winked and
joked about improvements in his social life when he announced he
was going to the almost exclusively female Mount Holyoke College
for a year.
   Life at the school of 2,000 women, however, has been no joke for
Johnson.
   ``I felt like the ultimate minority,'' he said. ``It's not quite
so fun as you might think.''
   Fellow male student Alex Ommaya still gets school mail addressed
to ``Miss Ommaya'' after more than a year at Mount Holyoke. One
recent missive reminded him that he will need a white dress for the
Alumni Day parade later this month.
   ``I'm thinking of wearing a toga,'' said Ommaya.
   Johnson and Ommaya comprise two-thirds of the entire male
student population at the exclusive school. The other third is Josh
Winchell, who is spending a semester there as an exchange student
from Wesleyan University in Middletown, Conn.
   Even the ebullient, resilient Winchell found his first week at
Mount Holyoke slightly rough. ``But I have two sisters, so I didn't
see this as a major obstacle,'' he said.
   The 151-year-old undergraduate college in rural western
Massachusetts has long resisted the tide of coeducation that has
swept other single-sex schools, but does admit men to its graduate
programs in the sciences.
   The school also allows men from four nearby colleges _ Amherst,
Hampshire, Smith and the University of Massachusetts _ to take
classes and has an exchange program with 11 other Northeast
colleges.
   But Mount Holyoke sends more students off to coed campuses than
it brings in, said Dean of Studies Sarah Sutherland. She said male
exchange students consequently stand out, but ``if this institution
has any mission, ultimately it is the obliteration of
discrimination on the grounds of sex.''
   Ommaya, 23, of Bethesda, Md., was admitted to Mount Holyoke's
two-year graduate program in neuroscience after graduating from
Vassar College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y. He will be the lone male to
graduate from the school this month.
   He also is the only man to head a student campus organization.
He said he was appointed to run the office that provides student
entertainment because he was the only applicant.
   He did so well at perking up a reportedly dismal night life _ by
opening a piano bar and holding casino and masquerade parties _
that he was honored by the Student Government Association for his
contribution to the college.
   Ommaya said he wasn't aware Mount Holyoke was a women's school
when he applied after reading about the neuroscience program in a
catalog that neglected to mention men were scarce on campus.
   ``Vassar is also a Seven Sisters school, so I should have known,
but Mount Holyoke is not one of the sisters you remember,'' he
said. Vassar is now coeducational.
   He said an admissions officer's questions tipped him off. ``She
kept asking me why I wanted to go here, what I would get as a male
from it. I finally figured out why when I looked it up in
Barron's,'' a college guide.
   The school's single-sex status did not dissuade him. ``It was
just an interesting factor.''
   The first few months, however, were tough. Ommaya was stared at
during dormitory meals, stopped and questioned on his way to class.
``It's the first time I've ever been discriminated against as a
white man,'' he said.
   In time, the stares stopped and he developed friendships, but he
longed for male company and, like some lonely women, began to
ponder obsessively the question ``How can I meet men?''
   ``I had to keep myself from walking up to men and saying, `Hi,
how're you doin', do you want to be friends?''' he said.
   The son of a Mount Holyoke English professor, Johnson came to
the school for a tuition-free year to catch up on physics and other
courses before returning to Swarthmore College outside Philadelphia.
   The 20-year-old junior said he wasn't prepared for the
overwhelmingly female environment. ``I got tremendously freaked out
at first just sitting in classes full of women,'' he said. ``But
people were very nice, actually.''
   Nevertheless, his experience at Mount Holyoke has soured him
permanently on women's colleges.
   ``I think that to spend the years of 18 to 22 on a campus with
all women _ it's got to be a little bit strange,'' he said.
</TEXT>
