<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FirehouseTavern     05-01 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firehouse Tavern,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Department Tavern Closes After 45 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the alarm sounded in the Chicago Fire
Department's ``9th Division,'' no one raced for the firetrucks.
   Most of the firefighters only laughed, cheered and raised their
beer bottles when the lights and the sirens went off for the last
time. Others took a final slide down the brass pole.
   The occasion was the retirement of Jim Rzonca, 74, ending his
watch as the department's favorite saloonkeeper after 45 years of
chasing firetrucks and washing the smoke out of firefighters'
throats at his Jim's Fire Barn.
   ``Jim's been to more fires than most firemen,'' said Capt. Jim
Dean, president of the Chicago Fire Officials Association. ``And he
probably knows more about the Fire Department than most fire
chiefs.''
   Dean was among several hundred firefighters and other friends
who crowded the tavern late Saturday in honor of the closing,
standing three deep at the long bar and clustered around the free
buffet of Italian and Polish specialities.
   ``I've been coming here ever since I joined the Fire Department
in 1965, and my father, who was a captain, too, came here before
me,'' said Dean. ``There aren't nine official divisions in the
department, but we call this place the `9th Division' as sort of a
code name.
   ``Jim keeps a fire scanner going behind the bar and knows where
every unit is going. But sometimes we had to tend bar ourselves
because he was out chasing fires.''
   Rzonca fell in love with firefighting as a boy when he delivered
newspapers to the local firehouse. But his only official fire
department job was for three months with the fire marshal's office
before he and his wife, Stella, opened the tavern. Now their two
sons are firefighters.
   The tavern walls were covered with fire memorabilia: model
firetrucks, oxygen masks, diving tanks, photographs of notable
fires, badges and helmets.
   While posing for a photographer on closing night, Rzonca donned
a helmet from the special force that protected the Century of
Progress Exposition in 1933.
   ``I have helmets from almost every battalion in Chicago, most of
the suburbs and plenty from other cities and states,'' said Rzonca.
``People make jokes about visiting firemen, but I always treated
them like real guests.
   ``I can go to the fire department in just about any city and be
treated well myself _ especially if I take the time to be nice to
the firehouse cook.''
   One special glass case contained helmets and dress caps from
firefighters who died on duty or from injuries suffered fighting
fires.
   ``I had some very sad experiences not being a real firefighter
and being around these men all the time,'' he said.
   On a lighter note, Rzonca remembered a succession of dogs that
divided their lives between various firehouses and his tavern.
Most, in keeping with tradition, were Dalmatians.
   ``One engine company dropped off `Buster.' Said he was so dumb
he couldn't be trained,'' he recalled. ``I taught him to pose for
pictures with his head and paws hanging out of the hook-and-ladder
window. I even got him to wear football shoulderpads.''
   Rzonca admitted he really didn't want to hang up his own helmet.
   ``Oh, I'm closing all right,'' Rzonca said. ``But after a month
or so, I wouldn't be suprised if I didn't open up again as a
three-nights-a-week private club _ firefighters only.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
