<HEAD>Renowned Italian Actor Dead At 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paolo Stoppa, one of Italy's foremost stage and
screen character actors, died Sunday at his home, his doctor said.
He was 81.
   Stoppa suffered from leukemia for two years and died of
complications of the disease, said Dr. Giuseppe Pappa.
   Since 1935, Stoppa appeared in dozens of Italian and
international films. He also founded a theater that employed the
noted director Luchino Visconti in the early stages of his career.
   Stoppa played Pope Alexander III in ``Becket.'' Some of his
other film credits include ``Rocco And His Brothers,'' ``Behold A
Pale Horse'' and ``Once Upon A Time In The West.''
   He had not made a film since 1982 and illness had kept him in
his house since Feb. 18.
   The funeral was scheduled for Tuesday in the Church of Saint
Eustachio.
