<1ST_LINE>u p AM-JacksonPlan Bjt   05-01 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson Plan, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Takes More Combative Tone As Dukakis Delegate Lead Widens</HEAD>
<HEAD>By RITA BEAMISH</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, striking a combative stance as
he loses ground to Democratic presidential rival Michael Dukakis,
plans to campaign in every state remaining on the primary calendar,
presenting himself as the clear alternative to the Republicans.
   In the face of Dukakis' widening lead in the delegate count _
he's ahead by roughly 400 _ Jackson vows he won't give up his
fight. And he won't entertain what he calls ``absurd'' talk about
his going for a vice presidential spot.
   Focusing heavily on delegate-rich California, Jackson says he
will not slacken his campaign pace, and will stage advertising
campaigns in each of the upcoming states.
   ``You can't win unless you go there,'' said campaign manager
Gerald Austin. ``We're going to be taking our message everywhere.''
   Austin's tone was emphatic in the wake of Jackson's own public
contradiction of comments Austin made last week. In published
remarks, Austin downplayed prospects of winning the nomination and
spoke more in terms of Jackson's achievements in broadening the
Democratic Party.
   Although it appears a unlikely that Jackson can overtake Dukakis
in delegates before the primaries end June 7, Jackson himself is
telling his supporters not to give up hope.
   The last big primaries are June 7 in California and New Jersey,
and the campaign for so-called super delegates continues. The
convention begins July 18.
   Jackson's still-developing schedule calls for him to spend a day
each in Montana, New Mexico, Nebraska and West Virginia, which also
hold late contests.
   He tentatively plans three days in New Jersey, four days in
Oregon and the rest of the time in California, where 314 Democratic
delegates are up for grabs on June 7, said campaign political
director Frank Watkins.
   Austin said Jackson will continue to appeal to the ethnic
groups, gays and the economically struggling who have been the
focus of his campaign so far.
   While continuing to rail agains the Reagan administration and
stress the importance of a Democratic victory, Jackson will
increasingly emphasize distinctions between himself and Dukakis on
the issues, Austin said.
   Jackson unveiled that strategy this past week. In contrast to
his earlier aversion to criticizing Democratic rivals, Jackson is
portraying Dukakis as an uninspiring candiate who is lacking a
clear commitment to reverse Reagan's economic programs.
   Austin and other campaing aides declined to discuss what states
they expect to do best in, but Austin said Jackson should do better
in Tuesday's Ohio primary than he does in Indiana, with a primary
the same day, because Jackson has spent little time in Indiana.
   He filed delegate slates in only 18 of Ohio's 21 congressional
districts, but Austin said the campaign is contesting every one of
those districts.
   Jackson's buying up of $400,000 worth of air time in Ohio
includes a new ad that will attack Dukakis as wiling only to
``manage'' Reaganomics, not to bring about real economic change.
   Jackson is also becoming increasingly sensitive about his aides
commenting publicly on strategy. Campaign aides have been
close-mouthed following Jackson's reaction to the Austin remarks
about his campaign prospects.
   ``I'm not commenting today,'' said longtime Jackson aide Frank
Watkins, when asked about the campaign game plan.
   ``He doesn't like poeple boxing him in on options,'' said one
Jackson adviser. ``He is his own person'' and has his own sense of
where his campaign is going, said the source, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   The Jackson camp expects to have a significant impact on the
Democratic party platform and discussions on that should begin
soon, aides said.
   One adviser even said he has no doubt that the party will allow
the Jackson campaign, which has taken the lead in shaping campaign
issues, to write the platform.
   The camapign recently won a court victory in New Jersey that
makes it easier for people to vote for for Jackson and his
delegates by pulling the voting lever just once instead of several
times. But Austin said he does not envision any new legal
challenges at this time.
   However, he added: ``Things can come up.'' Many states have
delegate-selection processes that continue after their initial
primaries or caucuses.
</TEXT>
