<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrideofBaltimore     05-01 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pride of Baltimore,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pride of Baltimore II Launched With Fanfare</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a 200-ton crane lifted the clipper
schooner Pride of Baltimore II into the Inner Harbor to the cheers
of thousands, this rejuvenated city got ``a new clipper, but the
old Pride,'' Mayor Kurt L. Schmoke said.
   The rebuilding of the city's goodwill ambassador ship, whose
predecessor sank 240 miles north of Puerto Rico in a microburst of
wind and rain on May 14, 1986, came about because of intense public
pressure, the mayor acknowledged.
   ``Without your help the Pride of Baltimore II would have
remained just a wish and a promise,'' Schmoke told people jammed
into every available vantage point near the Pride and on historic
Federal Hill overlooking the harbor.
   ``The Pride of Baltimore is a labor of community love,'' the
mayor said. ``The Pride in Baltimore ... has been uninterrupted
from the very start.''
   The outpouring of public sentiment _ which changed the minds of
officials initially opposed to building a second clipper schooner _
was acknowledged in bittersweet ceremonies Saturday, when Baltimore
dedicated the new vessel in memory of all Marylanders lost at sea.
   Four crew members died in the 1986 sinking of the original Pride.
   The ceremony included music by the red-costumed U.S. Marine
Band, a procession of Maryland schoolchildren bearing symbols of
their areas of the state, the firing of muskets by the Fort McHenry
Guard and a parade of Tall Ships.
   The first Pride, which promoted Baltimore and Maryland in
harbors around the world, was launched by the same Bethlehem Steel
crane known as Big Red in 1977.
   The new Pride, 110 tons of finely crafted hardwoods and ballast
without the masts and engines to be added in coming months, took
form at a waterfront construction site.
   Gov. William Donald Schaefer, Baltimore's mayor when the first
Pride was launched and when it was lost, said he had two wishes for
the new vessel. ``God smile on this ship. God keep that crew
safe,'' he said, his voice breaking.
   The launch, attended by former Pride crewmembers and two
survivors of the Pride sinking, also included the ceremonial
ringing of the Pride bell, produced by the McShane Bell Foundry Co.
Inc. of Glen Burnie and presented to the Pride of Baltimore
organization by U.S. Rep. Helen Delich Bentley, R-Md.
   ``We are here today to christen a unique vessel ... that will
serve as goodwill ambassador ... a vessel that will also serve as a
living memorial to Captain Armin Elsaesser III, Nina Francesca
Schack, Vincent Lazzaro and Barry Duckworth, who lost their lives
on that fateful day in May 1986,'' she said.
   Moments later, with shipwrights guiding thick yellow cables by
hand and derrick operator Bill Ward working from the crane control
booth, the Pride made the short journey from the construction site
to the water accompanied by wild cheering, cannon fire and fireboat
sprays.
   The ship will undergo sea trials in the fall.
</TEXT>
