<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AmericanRabbi 1stLd-Writethru   05-01 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Rabbi, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0711 ,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frustrated American Rabbi Leaving East Germany</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Neuman didn't' to UPDATE with Neuman saying
he'll return to Illinois; SUBS grafs 15-16, `During the...over
there''' to CORRECT that newspaper is West German. Picks up 17th
graf, ```A large...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American who is the only rabbi for East
Germany's tiny Jewish community said Sunday he's leaving the
communist country because of intolerable working conditions caused
by attempts to silence him.
   Isaac Neuman, a Polish-born survivor of Auschwitz and nine other
Nazi concentration camps, said he will depart for good by year's
end.
   In an interview at his East Berlin apartment, the controversial
65-year-old rabbi talked of interference from Jewish leadership and
objected to government treatment of his religious community.
``There regularly are informers at every worship service and at
every class,'' he said.
   Neuman became the only rabbi for the nation's 350 officially
registered Jews on Sept. 23. He was the nation's first rabbi in 21
years.
   About half of East Berlin's estimated 200 Jews are more than 60
years old. Most were locked up, went into hiding or fled the
country during the Third Reich, Neuman said. Some came back later
from the United States and other places.
   The rabbi received great press attention in the West and in East
Germany when he came to be their spiritual leader.
   Now, he says he will leave later this month. ``It's conceivable
it is for good, but I may be back in September,'' he said. ``I have
no intention of being here beyond 1988, because the situation is
too impossible to work.''
   He said he would return to his home in Champaign, Ill.
   Neuman went to the United States in 1950. After his studies, he
served as rabbi in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, from 1961 to 1974, and in
Champaign, from 1974 to 1987.
   He had retired before taking the job in East Berlin. He said he
had always viewed it as a ``temporary assignment.''
   Neuman said leadership of the local Jewish community kept a
close watch on his activities. He said there might be ``orders from
somewhere to keep me under control.''
   He also said there have been efforts within the Jewish community
to silence him. He was hampered in setting up religious education
classes for adults, he said.
   Other frustrations included a monthly Jewish community bulletin
that omitted mention of last month's anniversary of the Warsaw
Ghetto's Jewish uprising against the Nazis in World War II. In
addition, Neuman complained of an East German cartoonist who he
said plies anti-Semitic themes.
   During the rabbi's stay, he also took to task the editor of one
of the official government newspapers for reporting on clashes in
Israel. He came away without a correction or retraction.
   Neuman, in turn, has been criticized by Germans.
   ``The Jewish community in East Berlin is startled by the
unconventionality and the independence of their rabbi,'' the
authoritative West German Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper
said in a profile on April 19. The newspaper also said the
``temperamental rabbi'' had threatened to leave in the past, even
though ``he has things well over there.''
   ``A large apartment and a car are provided for him,'' the
Frankfurter Allgemeine said.
   Neuman is paid by East Berlin's Jewish community, which receives
funds from the communist government.
   Neuman says he has been careful as a foreigner to avoid
involvement in the nation's growing dissident movement, openly
supported by parts of the Lutheran Church.
   But he expressed frustration with the government's stance toward
the Jewish community. He said it should help renovate the
dilapidated Jewish community building.
   Neuman also said most Jews in East Berlin will be sorry to see
him go.
   ``But there were will be a few (other people) who will be glad,
because then they have it under control again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
