<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Hospitals-Labor     05-01 0131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hospitals-Labor,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Vote Under Way for Seven Bay Area Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital workers at seven medical
facilities in the San Francisco Bay area overwhelmingly favored a
strike resolution growing out of their demand for better health
benefits.
   In the first round of voting on Saturday, 95 percent approved
the strike authorization, according to Jennifer Fleming,
spokeswoman for Local 250 of the Hospital and Healthcare Workers
Union.
   More voting for the union's 1,700 members is scheduled Monday.
   The resolution is a 10-day notice that the nurses, housekeepers,
laundry workers, technicians and food-service employees will walk
off their jobs unless the dispute is settled. The union's contract
expired Sunday morning.
   The hospitals have proposed that workers pick up nearly $1,200 a
year of their own health care costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
