<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CardboardRegatta     05-01 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cardboard Regatta,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massive Cardboard Barge Steals Show At Regatta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Structural Integrity'' wasn't much to
look at, but the massive cardboard barge set a record for the
largest crew at the 15th annual Great Cardboard Boat Regatta.
   Several crew members steadied the sides of the 20-foot by
20-foot cardboard flatbed Saturday and chanted ``More! More!
More!'' while a steady line of bodies poured off the dock and into
the boat.
   Then, as if a portion of earth had broken off into Campus Lake
at Southern Illinois University, the 56-member crew just floated
away _ sort of.
   The official count on the craft, however, was 58 people because
halfway through the course ``Integrity'' barreled over the top of
another cardboard boat and two capsized riders fished from the lake
were added to the ``Integrity's'' crew.
   In the end, ``Structural Integrity'' buried the former record of
34 people on a cardboard boat set in Du Quoin last year.
   It also tried the patience of regatta Commodore Richard Archer,
who growled, ``Get that thing outta the way!'' when it was blocking
other boats in the race.
   Massive barges like ``Integrity'' are not much to look at, next
to some of the slickly engineered cardboard marvels entered in
Saturday's race.
   But the three mammoth barges carrying a total of 129 riders were
definitely the show-stealers and the crowd-pleasers at the 15th
annual regatta. The crowd of 20,000 people seemed to relish the
wonder of it all.
   Patty Mullen, who held the old record for the biggest crew,
managed to find 38 fellow navigators _ called the ``Murphysboro Hot
Tub Club'' _ to take her personally made craft through the course
at a swift, synchronized clip.
   ``I sent out invitations to everyone I could think of,'' Mullen
said. ``I had no idea how many people were coming.''
   The group _ which also included a dog _ was given this year's
Team Award by regatta judges.
   The third entry in the Battle of the Barge managed 33 people,
but couldn't muster the full trip. The back end of the 40-foot-long
ship fell off at midpoint in the race and the stern began sinking.
   The rest of the boat followed, inch by inch.
   Saturday's crowd was probably the largest in the regatta's
15-year history, organizers said. The 206 boats entered also set a
record for the most participants.
</TEXT>
