<2ND_LINE>AM-Portland Implosion,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten-Story Building Imploded into Pile of Rubble</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PD1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-story building came down in a loud
blast and a huge cloud of dust Sunday after engineers set off 185
explosives inside the 81-year-old downtown structure.
   It was the first time the implosion method of demolition had
been used in Portland. Hundreds of people lined nearby rooftops and
streets to witness the early morning blast that brought the Corbett
Building down in 5 seconds.
   Officials said there were no injuries and no damage to nearby
buildings. Only a large pile of rubble and a 12-square-block cloud
of dust remained after the building dropped into its basement on
the block behind the historic Pioneer Courthouse.
   The building is being removed to make way for the three-block
Pioneer Place project, which will feature a new department store
and retail shops.
   Some office workers in nearby buildings held parties and had
champagne breakfasts to celebrate the implosion.
</TEXT>
