<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     05-01 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Facing Uphill Fight In Tuesday's Ohio Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson, campaigning in the face of polls indicating he trails far
behind rival Michael Dukakis in Ohio, said Sunday that he is
``pulling'' Dukakis in his direction on important domestic and
foreign policy issues.
   Jackson brushed off a reporter's question about surveys in the
Akron Beacon Journal and the Columbus Dispatch that suggested he
trails Dukakis by a 3-1 margin.
   `Our campaign of hope continues,'' he said. ``Our support base
gets broader and bigger every day.''
   Jackson vowed to continue his campaign past Tuesday's election
and through to June 7, the end of the primary season.
   Preaching Sunday morning at Olivet Baptist Church, Jackson said
he intended to ``turn up the heat'' in the next five weeks.
   He said he has been asked whether he was pushing Dukakis to come
around to his point of view on key issues.
   ``I'm pulling him,'' Jackson called. ``I am out in front on a
plan to stop the flow of drugs...I am pulling him.''
   ``I'm not pushing folks behind me,'' he said. ``I'm leading
them.''
   Jackson has been portraying Dukakis as unwilling to make strong
statements about what he would do as president. He said Sunday that
leaders cannot afford to play it so safe.
   ``The kitchen is clean and cool,'' he said. ``Ain't nothing
cooking.''
   Jackson preached Sunday sermons to two strikingly contrasting
congregations _ one an all-white audience at Lakewood United
Methodist Church where Gov. Richard Celeste introduced the
candidate, and the other in the all-black Olivet Baptist Church,
which was filled with the sound of a gospel choir.
   Celeste is neutral in the Democratic race and would not say who
would get his vote. He told reporters that both Democrats are
``tremendous candiates.'' But he nodded toward Jackson and said:
``This message right here is the winning message.''
   Jackson spoke about the poverty and homelessness in America,
saying the nation must fight to change the policies that keep
working people and children in poverty.
   Reciting statistics about the increase in the numbers of poor
and homeless people over the last 20 years, Jackson said his goal
is `to comfort the disturbed but also disturb the comfortable.''
   He said budget austerity should not be used as an excuse to hold
back on spending to help the poor.
   ``Don't give up. Leaders have to think ... You've got to have
common sense'' to make cuts in some areas and spend in others, he
said.
   Jackson later traveled to Columbus for a pair of fund-raisers.
</TEXT>
