<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HungerWalk     05-01 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunger Walk,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walk For Hunger Draws 30,000 Trekkers In The Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 30,000 people walked 20 miles in the rain
Sunday and earned donors' pledges of more than $3 million to feed
the hungry, the organizer of 19th annual Walk for Hunger said.
   ``This community is so committed,'' said Shoshana Pakciarcz,
executive director of Project Bread, which sponsors the annual
fund-raising trek.
   She said the walk is the nation's largest such effort to raise
money to feed the hungry. Last year's event drew 25,000 people and
raised $1.7 million.
   ``When you get really sore, I always say `Jesus walked _ if he
could do it, so could I,'' said Donna Tilton, 46, of Wilmington,
laughing at the end of her five-hour trek.
   Each walker collected pledges from donors who promised to pay a
certain amount for every mile walked. Walkers started at Boston
Common and passed eight checkpoints on the circular route through
Newton, Cambridge and Boston.
   Mrs. Tilton and her husband, Bob, raised $500 between them. They
came armed with six pairs of socks, foot powder, camera and snacks.
   They said they derived encouragement from their fellow
travelers: a blind man led by a sighted friend, a ``walker'' on
roller skates, small children and the elderly, and a former drug
addict who now works in drug rehabilitation.
   ``It was just a good bunch of people, doing something for those
less fortunate,'' said Tilton, 47. ``The hungry will always be with
us.''
   Ms. Pakciarcz gave credit for the increased participation and
pledges to the event's simplicity.
   ``Hunger is such a basic, basic thing. A nation this wealthy
shouldn't have anybody hungry,'' Ms. Pakciarcz said. ``One out of
four children under 6 is poor and hungry and people are just saying
no to hunger.
   ``People come out because we give them an opportunity to do
something they can do, not something abstract.''
   She also said participation has grown since Reagan was elected.
   ``In eight years of the Reagan administration, these (welfare)
programs were all kept even or cut. The walk has grown
substantially since 1980,'' she said.
   Ninety percent of the contributions will go to soup kitchens,
homeless shelters and urban gardens across Massachusetts, and the
rest is sent overseas. For instance, some of the money will go to
build an oven for a village in Haiti.
</TEXT>
