<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChicagoSlurs     05-01 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Slurs,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Angry Over Mayor's Aide's Racial Slurs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chicago Mayor Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry religious leaders said Sunday that an aide
to Mayor Eugene Sawyer should be fired for making comments they
viewed as racial and religious slurs against Jews and Christians.
   But Monroe Anderson, the mayor's press secretary, said there was
only a ``very, very remote'' chance Sawyer would fire Steve Cokely,
an aide who works as a liaison with black nationalist groups.
   In tape-recorded lectures before followers of Nation of Islam
leader Louis Farrakhan, Cokely contended that Jews have a ``secret
society'' and plan to control the world.
   Cokely, 35, also criticized the late Mayor Harold Washington and
presidential candidate Jesse Jackson for employing Jewish advisers,
and he attacked Christianity by calling the cross a symbol of white
supremacy, the Chicago Tribune reported.
   Monsignor John Egan, director of community affairs for DePaul
University, said ``as long as Cokely is there, there is a cancer in
the (mayor's) administration.''
   Michael Kotzin, regional director of the Anti-Defamation League
of B'nai B'rith, said Sunday that Cokely ``espouses positions that
malign the members of the community in ways that echo some of the
most traditional forms of gutter-level bigotry.''
   ``Any person who expresses these kinds of thoughts should not be
on the city payroll,'' said Kotzin, who said he has heard
recordings of the lectures.
   ``Words aren't mere words, especially words of these kinds. They
truly have the potential to do damage,'' Kotzin said in a telephone
interview.
   Kotzin said he met the mayor four weeks ago and talked with him
about Cokely's ``baseless anti-Jewish and anti-white charges.''
   Anderson, the mayor's spokesman, said Sawyer had decided ``to
talk to Cokely and tell him to tune down his rhetoric,'' but had no
plans to fire him from his $35,568-a-year job as coordinator of
special projects.
   Questioned about the lectures, Cokely said he is not
anti-semitic and that his role as a community activist is to
provoke debate.
   ``I'm responsible for debating various points of view in my role
as a consciousness-raiser,'' he said.
   Rev. David Whitermore, executive director of the Church
Federation of Greater Chicago, said that, based on ``the contacts
that I have had with the mayor in many church services, I can't
conceive of him backing or endorsing anything that has been reputed
to have been said (by Cokely).''
</TEXT>
