<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fistfights, Walkout Mar District Convention in North Carolina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISBURG, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district GOP convention here turned
into a melee when supporters of presidential candidate Pat
Robertson clashed with backers of Vice President George Bush,
officials said.
   The confrontation came as the district's Republicans were
selecting three delegates to the Republican National Convention in
New Orleans in August.
   Order was restored only after the Franklin County sheriff _ a
Democrat _ and a platoon of deputies arrived at the National Guard
Armory in Louisburg, where the 4th District convention was being
held Saturday night.
   No one was seriously injured, said Sheriff Arthur E. Johnson.
   He said the trouble began when Robertson supporters became angry
when it became apparent that supporters of Vice President George
Bush were not going to allow two county delegations controlled by
Robertson backers to be seated.
   ``This is a fraud,'' shouted Richard Hines of Wake County, the
leader of the Robertson forces. ``This is a railroad ...You are
either going to run this convention correctly or we are going to
run it.''
   A group of Robertson supporters then rushed the podium, and
pandemonium broke out.
   There were at least three fistfights as the Bush and Robertson
forces battled for control, and Calvin Vincent of Franklin County,
the convention's sergeant of arms, was thrown to the floor,
district chairman Larry Norman said.
   After the confrontation, Robertson supporters walked out and
held a separate convention to elect their own three delegates.
   Norman said he was ``very, very, very disappointed'' in the way
things turned out.
   ``I knew we would have a problem,'' Norman said. ``I really
didn't expect anybody to get out of the bounds of civility and
begin attacking people.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Some Ohio Ballots Won't List Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Ohioans who go the polls Tuesday to
cast votes for their party's presidential nominee won't see the
name of their candidate on the ballot.
   Vice President George Bush, the all-but-certain Republican
nominee, is on all the ballots, as is Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, the front-runner for the Democratic nomination.
   But Democrat Jesse Jackson missed getting on the ballot as a
result of procedural problems in three of the 21 congressional
district ballots.
   Jackson was left off the ballots in the 5th District in
northwest Ohio, the 10th in southeast Ohio and the 13th in
northeast Ohio due to failures by his backers to meet pre-election
filing requirements.
   In those districts, voters will see the name of Sen. Albert Gore
of Tennessee, who suspended his campaign April 21 but technically
remained in the race and is on all ballots.
   Former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart, who dropped from the race, is
still on the ballot in the 10th and 13th Districts, among others.
His 10th and 13th District delegates have promised to support
Jackson if Hart gets enough votes to qualify them as delegates.
Secretary of State Sherrod Brown says there is no statutory basis
for them to do so, but that the Democratic Party could allow it.
   Hart would have to get 15 percent of the votes to get any
delegates in those districts, and he did not do that well in any
state in which he actively campaigned.
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who suspended his campaign a month
ago, will be on the ballot in some scattered districts, such as the
4th in northwest Ohio.
</TEXT>
