<1ST_LINE>r p AM-OhioPolls     05-01 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ohio Polls,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Indicate Dukakis Holds Big Lead Over Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis holds a
nearly 3-1 lead over Democratic presidential opponent Jesse Jackson
in Ohio's primary contest, two polls suggested Sunday.
   A poll published in The Columbus Dispatch said Dukakis was the
favorite among 62 percent of the 1,974 registered Democrats who
responded to the newspaper's statewide mail survey last week, while
Jackson was the choice of 24 percent. The remaining 14 percent
supported other candidates.
   A University of Akron poll published in the Akron Beacon Journal
gave Dukakis a margin over Jackson of 62 percent to 22 percent
among Democrats who said they were likely to vote.
   The telephone poll of 926 registered Ohio voters was taken
between April 20 and Saturday. It was paid for by the Beacon
Journal and television stations WCMH in Columbus and WKYC in
Cleveland.
   The Columbus poll had an estimated margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points on each result, while the margin for the
Akron poll was 3.5 points.
   The Akron poll indicated that Jackson was finding it hard to
broaden his support beyond a solid core of black supporters. Eleven
percent of white Democrats surveyed in the poll chose Jackson; 82
percent of black Democrats supported him.
   Jackson told reporters in Columbus Sunday he was paying no
attention to the polls.
   ``I'm focusing on our mission, which is to keep America strong
and make America better, and our message, stop drugs from coming
in, stop jobs from going out, re-invest in America,'' Jackson said.
   In Akron, Dukakis quickly shrugged off the favorable survey, and
continued a campaign pace that indicated he was taking nothing for
granted.
   ``I know there's a poll out today. Please ignore it,'' Dukakis
said. ``Pollsters do not vote.''
</TEXT>
