<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-LePen     05-01 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Le Pen,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extreme Right Leader Refuses Outright Endorsement of Chirac</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rightist leader Jean-Marie Le Pen told thousands of
his followers Sunday not to help re-elect Socialist President
Francois Mitterrand but he refused to formally endorse conservative
Premier Jacques Chirac.
   Mitterrand and Chirac were the top vote getters in the April 24
presidential balloting and are the only two candidates in the
runoff election next Sunday.
   Le Pen called his anti-immigrant National Front the
``avant-garde'' of France and told his supporters to organize so
``the next time the people will have the last word.''
   About 30,000 people marched in a rain through the heart of Paris
to the rally in the Tuileries Gardens. The demonstration was called
by the National Front to honor Joan of Arc, the party's patron
saint who led the fight in the 15th century against English
invaders.
   ``We are in a position of choosing between the bad and the
worst,'' Le Pen told the crowd in an hour-long speech.
   Mitterrand is the worst and Chirac is the ``residual
candidate,'' he said.
   Le Pen listed three possibilities for his followers: Stay home,
vote for Chirac ``to avoid the worst'' or decide at the last minute
depending on Chirac's statements in the final week of the campaign.
   ``If Jacques Chirac is defeated, he has only himself, his
friends and his allies to blame,'' Le Pen said. ``We have no
responsibility in the voting.''
   Dozens of groups from around France, including monarchists
waving fleur-de-lis flags and war veterans, filed past Le Pen and
the Joan of Arc statue near the Tuileries.
   More than 30,000 people rallied in two counter-marches organized
by different unions to protest Le Pen's rally on May Day, the
traditional territory of organized labor.
   In the past, Le Pen has led marches on May 8, the day
commemorating Joan of Arc. But since the presidential runoff
election is set for May 8 the National Front held the rally a week
early.
   Authorities had feared conflict between the National Front rally
and the labor marches no incidents were reported.
   Le Pen, who won 14.4 percent of the first-round vote on April
24, was eliminated along with seven other candidates.
   But the showing by his extreme right party weakened the
traditional right, and Chirac will need National Front votes to
defeat Mitterrand.
   In the first round, Mitterrand won 34 percent and Chirac
received just under 20 percent. All polls show Mitterrand winning
easily on May 8, drawing between 53 and 57 percent of the votes.
   Since April 24, Chirac has tried to attract Le Pen's followers,
stressing the need to stop immigration and conserve France's
national identity.
   Le Pen claims that France is being drained economically,
socially and culturally because of immigrants from its former
colonies in North Africa.
</TEXT>
