<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Kirk     05-01 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kirk,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Democratic Chairman Assails Reagan Administration Ethics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic National Committee chairman
Paul Kirk on Sunday attacked the ethical standards of the Reagan
administration and challenged the Republicans' nominee-apparent,
George Bush, to speak out on the subject.
   ``When the attorney general of the United States, the country's
No. 1 law enforcement officer, can be cited as `Public Suspect No.
1,' something is wrong,'' Kirk told an audience at the University
of Notre Dame.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese has been the target of a lengthy
criminal investigation, but has not been charged with any crime.
   Kirk said Bush, who has a numerical lock on the Republican
presidential nomination, has failed to consider whether the public
trust is being upheld by the administration in light of criminal
investigations of Meese.
   ``For George Bush, the only calculation is whether the
embarrassment will be so great that his own political opportunities
as a candidate will be undermined,'' Kirk said.
   Kirk's comments came in a Law Day speech delivered the day
before Bush was to make a final campaign swing through South Bend
before Indiana's primary election Tuesday.
   Kirk read a list of 11 top Reagan administration officials,
including Meese, who have resigned under fire or been investigated,
indicted or convicted.
   ``The hall of shame of the administration is crowded, but there
are profiles in courage as well,'' he said, citing two Justice
Department officials who quit, reportedly in protest over Meese's
continued tenure.
   ``But regrettably, among those profiles we cannot include the
president, who waves it off, nor Vice President George Bush, who is
not troubled enough to comment or sufficiently outraged to get
involved,'' he said.
   ``There comes a time when personal cronyism and loyalty to
individuals, and loyalty even to the highest office in the land,
must be replaced by a loyalty to public honor,'' he said.
   Since last May 11, Meese has been the subject of a criminal
investigation by a special prosecutor examining various matters
inlcuding Meese's assistance to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
   Kirk said Bush campaigners searching for skeletons in the closet
during Dukakis's terms as governor of Massachusetts will find
nothing comparable to the misdeeds of the Reagan administration.
   ``It's a no-win political tactic on their part,'' he said.
   Reagan has defended Meese and the Justice Department despite
being told by some resigning department officials that ``a deep
malaise'' had set in and that Meese should be indicted.
</TEXT>
