<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BananaSplit     05-01 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banana Split,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Claims Record For World's Longest Banana Split</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELINSGROVE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With 33,000 bananas, 2,500 gallons of
ice cream and 150 gallons of chocolate syrup, this town made a
4.5-mile banana split in a bid to regain a place in the Guinness
Book of World Records.
   ``Three. Two. One. Dig in!'' WGYL-AM program director Scott West
told about 24,000 people standing and sitting in front of their
one-foot sections of the 12.6 million calorie dessert Saturday
afternoon.
   Many had started eating.
   ``It was getting pretty soupy after a while,'' said Robert Linn
of New Berlin.
   ``It's something for the town to say, `When we work together,
anything is possible,''' said Kelly Stoops, a teacher who was in
charge of organizing the event to raise money for a community
development organization in Selinsgrove, a central Pennsylvania
town of 5,500.
   Selinsgrove set the Guinness record for the world's longest
banana street in 1982 with a 1.5-mile spectacle, but was overtaken
in 1983, by New York high school students, who in turn were outdone
by Zeta Beta Tau Sorority at Bowling Green University in Ohio,
which created a 4-mile banana split in 1985.
