<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0712 05-01 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Suspended After Palestinian Protester Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with 6 more wounded. Pickup
16th graf pvs ``Sunday's protests...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI C. RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army suspended an officer after troops
under his command shot and killed a Palestinian Sunday during a
stone-throwing demonstration in the occupied West Bank.
   Troops using live ammunition and rubber bullets also wounded 13
Arabs on Sunday, a ``day of confrontation'' called by leaders of
the uprising in the occupied territories. An Associated Press
photographer was hit by a rubber bullet and an Arab-thrown rock in
two separate incidents.
   In other developments:
   _Israel's chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, said a marked
decline in violent incidents in the last week showed the
5-month-old rebellion was waning.
   _Israeli Arabs in the biblical town of Nazareth dedicated their
May Day parade to the uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
``Palestine, two countries for two peoples,'' read banners carried
by some of the thousands of Arabs who gathered in the city.
   The fatal shooting occurred in the village of Fakua when
Palestinian demonstrators hurled rocks at soldiers who moved in to
clear away roadblocks, burning tires and Palestinian flags, an army
spokesman said.
   Palestinian officials at a clinic in Jenin identified the man
killed as 22-year-old Naim Yusuf Mahmoud Abu Farha.
   The army suspended the officer in command of the patrol, the
army spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity in keeping
with regulations.
   Military sources said they were investigating whether the
soldiers had been too quick to open fire.
   Abu Farha was the 176th Palestinian killed by Israelis in
violence since Dec. 8, the beginning of the uprising in the lands
Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war. Two Israelis
have been killed.
   Troops clashed with Arab protesters Sunday in four refugee camps
in the Gaza Strip and in at least two towns in the West Bank.
   In the Gaza Strip, an army spokesman said a 10-year-old boy from
the Khan Yunis refugee camp was admitted to Nasser hospital with a
gunshot wound. He said the army was investigating the incident.
   Hospital officials said two teenagers and a 22-year-old man
suffered bullet wounds in their legs after soldiers opened fire
during a demonstration in the Shati refugee camp.
   Arab witnesses and hospital officials said at least four Arabs
were injured by rubber bullets, two in the Khan Yunis refugee camp
and two in the Jabaliya refugee camp. The army said it was checking
the reports.
   In the West Bank, a Palestinian was shot and wounded at Beit
Sahour, near the town of Bethlehem, after he fled from an army
checkpoint, the army spokesman said.
   At Deir Azun, a village near Tulkarem in the West Bank, soldiers
opened fire after protesters blocked the road and threw stones, an
army spokesman reported. He said four Arabs were slightly wounded.
   AP photographer Laurent Rebours was hit in the back by a rubber
bullet as he photographed a stone-throwing incident at Beit Sahour
and by a rock thrown by Arab demonstrators in Ramallah.
   Sunday's protests were in response to a leaflet distributed last
week by Arab underground leaders. The leaflet called on
Palestinians to make May Day ``a day of confrontation with
occupation forces and demonstrations in the villages and the
cities.''
   The leaflet also called on Palestinians ``to strike the severest
blows'' against Israeli-appointed Arab officials who had not
resigned, as ordered by leaders of the rebellion.
   There was no word of any attacks on the officials.
   Shomron told Israel radio the rebellion was fading.
   ``In my opinion, the residents in the territories understand
today that there is no chance of success by this method of
intefadeh,'' he said, using the Arabic term for uprising.
   ``I think they have come to understand, on their own, that the
Arab countries are not helping, and although the great big world
does television stories, beyond this they will not get help,'' he
said.
   The CBS television bureau chief in Tel Aviv, Terry Plantinga,
said Sunday that the network would protest the beating of one of
its Israeli cameramen in the West Bank city of Nablus.
   Plantinga said a soldier struck cameraman Amnon Eventov with a
rifle and smashed the window of his car Saturday.
   It was the third time a CBS camera crew had been assaulted by
soldiers in the occupied territories since January, Plantinga said.
   In Tel Aviv, 200,000 Israelis and tourists from 25 countries
crowded the route of a two-mile May Day parade.
   The annual march was sponsored by the Histadrut Labor
Federation, the nationwide trade union, which is an ally of Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres' left-center Labor Party.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc boycotted
the festivities as too extravagant. Israel's budget has been
strained by the cost of extra forces in the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
