<HEAD>Manufacturer Delivers 100th B-1B to Air Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp. delivered
its 100th B-1B bomber to the Air Force over the weekend, the
company announced.
   The aircraft, completed two months early and within budget, was
delivered Saturday during ceremonies at the aircraft assembly
complex, company officials said in a statement.
   The firm signed contracts for development and production of the
plane Jan. 20, 1982. Rockwell delivered the first B-1B to the Air
Force at Edwards Air Force Base in October, 1984. The plane
delivered Saturday will join 16 others based at McConnell Air Force
Base near Wichita, Kan.
   B-1B bombers are in operation at four Strategic Air Command
bases: Dyess Air Force Base, Texas; Ellsworth Air Force Base, S.D.;
Grand Forks Air Force Base, N.D.; and McConnell.
