<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Ferries 1stLd-Writethru a0760 05-01 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ferries, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Sails Past British Pickets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with graf to UPDATE with ferry leaving Belgium for
return trip. Pickup 2nd graf pvs ``A crowd...''; INSERTS graf after
6th graf pvs ``He accompanied...'' with detail. Pickup 7th graf pvs
``The Pride...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ferry company crippled by a 13-week
walkout by its union workers sailed its first strike-breaking
vessel to Belgium Sunday and the ship then headed back to England.
   A group of spectators watched from the cliffs of Dover as the
blue and white Pride of Bruges, with the P and O European Ferries
emblem on its side, left the harbor and entered the English
Channel. It arrived about 4{ hours later in Zeebrugge, Belgium.
   The ferry carried about a dozen freight trucks, a handful of
passengers, and a crew of 80 defying the strike.
   Some pickets had taunted the crewmen with shouts of ``Scab!''
when they arrived early Sunday at the dock to board the Pride of
Bruges for the voyage to Zeebrugge. The crewmen were taken to the
vessel in four buses with a police escort.
   P and O Director Sir Jeffrey Sterling, addressing the crew on
board the ship before it sailed, said he would not accept
intimidation by strikers. ``We know what we are doing is right,''
he said.
   He accompanied the ferry in a helicopter as the vessel headed to
sea and met it in Zeebrugge when it moored.
   Despite threats that unions on the European continent would
refuse to handle P and O ferries, the Belgian mooring party worked
without hesitation. The ship later sailed for Dover carrying 50
vehicles and 117 passengers, P and O said.
   The Pride of Bruges and its sister ship, the Pride of Kent,
arrived at Dover on Saturday from the Dutch port of Rotterdam,
where they had been kept since the dispute began. Company officials
gave no indication Sunday when the Pride of Kent might sail.
   The National Union of Seamen is striking over a plan by P and O
to reduce staff, impose longer shifts and increase responsibilities
for workers. The company moves are aimed at cutting costs in
preparation for increased competition from the Channel Tunnel
between England and France, which is to open in 1993.
   Sam McCluskie, general secretary of the 24,400-member National
Union of Seamen, said a telex had been sent to every British ship
at sea calling for support for the strikers.
   The company fired 720 strikers last week and said 1,100 P and O
seamen had accepted its new terms. But union spokesman Colin
Bennett said Sunday that 180 of those who had agreed to work had
since withdrawn and ``are back on the right side.''
   The union said almost 5,000 members working at ports throughout
the country were now on strike because of the dispute. Some
strikers were sympathetic members of P and O's British channel
competitor, Sealink.
   Foreign ferries continued sailing, and Dover port authorities
said Sunday there was virtually no delay for tourist traffic. Truck
drivers were still subject to delays of up to 15 hours for
crossings to Calais, France, and Ostend, Belgium.
</TEXT>
