<HEAD>West German Train Sets New Speed Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS that only officials, no regular passengers, aboard train</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WUERZBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prototype of a new locomotive
broke the world speed record for trains Sunday, rail officials said.
   The West German train clocked a top speed of 243 mph on a new
track between Hanover and Wuerzburg.
   The speed beat the world record of 228 mph set in 1981 by
France's High-Speed Train.
   Aboard the train were Transport minister Juergen Warnke,
Research and Science Minister Heinz Riesenhuber and officials of
the federal railways. There were no regular passengers.
   The train is part of a program to provide faster service between
the West Germany's major cities.
