<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0772 05-01 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0772,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Talks Tough On Drugs, Crime; Blasts Meese</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf pvs, Earlier, at, to UPDATE
with Dukakis in Toledo</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis on Sunday called
George Bush ``a blank slate'' in a Republican administration that
has violated and ignored the law and said the vice president will
have to begin speaking out on those issues.
   Dukakis, who tried to brush aside a fresh poll showing him with
an overwhelming lead in Ohio's Democratic presidential primary,
took aim at Bush, the expected Republican nominee, on a day in
which he toured a police station in Akron, Ohio, to underscore his
criticism of the Reagan administration's efforts to fight crime and
drugs.
   At a news conference later in Cleveland, Dukakis said the nation
has gone through seven years under Reagan ``in which rule of law
and respect for the constitution have not been the order of the
day.''
   Asked to describe Bush's role, he said: ``I'm not sure I can
answer what that role has been, frankly, because he's such a blank
slate.
   ``One doesn't know. I hope we'll learn as time goes on. But
we've had repeated violations of law. We've had repeated efforts to
play fast and loose with the law, to ignore congressional
mandates,'' Dukakis said. ``You've got a Justice Department tht is
rapidly becoming a laughingstock, and I would assume at some point
he's going to speak out on those issues. Until now he has not.''
   Dukakis earlier walked through a Polish neighborhood of
Cleveland in a parade.
   Earlier, at the Akron police department, he spoke with officers
at their morning roll call, and examined confiscated weapons and
drugs.
   Later, in Toledo, Dukakis visited the county jail and met with
the Lucas County sheriff.
   ``If the law enforcement officers who we ask to risk their lives
in this fight aren't getting the support and training and equipment
and encouragement they need ... we're going to lose that fight,''
he said in Akron.
   Dukakis said the administration had cut back on spending to
combat drugs, and he attacked the administration for dealing with
drug dealers in the Iran-Contra affair, and with Panama strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``We have an administration that has been doing business with
the drug-running Panamanian dictator, that's been furnishing aid to
the Contras through convicted drug dealers that are doing time in
federal penitentiaries,'' he said.
   ``How do we tell our kids to say no to drugs when we have an
administration that can't say no to drugs and drug dealers?''
   Dukakis spoke on the steps of the Akron police station to a
small noontime crowd of about 150 people. The small size of his
audience was in contrast to the huge support shown for him in a
poll released Sunday by the Akron Beacon-Journal newspaper.
   That poll of Ohio residents showed Dukakis with a nearly 3-1
lead over Jesse Jackson _ 62 percent to 22 percent _ with 16
percent undecided and a 3.5 percent margin of error. The poll was
conducted over 10 days beginning April 20.
   Dukakis appeared with prominent local Democrats, including Rep.
Tom Sawyer, D-Ohio, and Mayor Don Plusquellic, who remain
officially neutral in the primary battle between Dukakis and
Jackson.
   Dukakis has repeatedly urged supporters to ignore the poll,
reminding them of his 1978 re-election loss and the penchant of his
favorite baseball team, the Boston Red Sox, for blowing big leads.
   ``I know there is a poll out today. Please ignore it,'' Dukakis
said. ``Forget about the polls. ... It is not over.''
   At the police station, Dukakis saw confiscated automatic
weapons, guns, switchblades, and an array of drugs including
cocaine and marijuana. he promised his support for local law
enforcement efforts and said Massachusetts had the largest drop in
crime, with one exception, of any state in the last several years.
   Dukakis renewed his denunciation of President Reagan's plans to
veto trade legislation because of a provision requiring companies
to give 60 days notice beford closing plants.
   In a fresh attack, he said that Secretary of State George
Shultz, as a labor economist 20 years ago had suggested in a book
that displaced workers need six months to a year to adjust to the
loss of their jobs.
   ``Maybe the secretary of state and president ought to have a
conversation,'' Dukakis said. ``and maybe the secretary can help
the White House understand the trauma and the agony and pain of
being laid off.''
</TEXT>
