<HEAD>Navy Says Six Dead, Four Injured In Wreck On U.S. Base</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Eds: Subs grafs 5-8 bgng: All the fatalities... with 5 grafs,
three sailors flown to burn center, other details. Pick up 9th
graf: ``The vehicle outran...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GUANTANAMO, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A speeding car smashed into a U.S. Navy
van at the Guantanamo Navy base, killing five sailors and their
driver and injuring four people, officials said Sunday.
   The car's driver, who is not a U.S. citizen, was charged with
six counts of manslaughter after the wreck Saturday night and was
under guard at the base hospital, said Lt. Cmdr. Aaron Long,
spokesman at Atlantic Fleet headquarters in Norfolk, Va.
   Identities of the dead and injured were not immediately
available, said base spokesman Lt. Bob Hines.
   ``There was a fire involved in the accident,'' Hines said by
telephone. ``It's making identification (of the bodies) difficult.''
   Long said the names of the dead and injured would not be
released until their relatives had been notified.
   He said the three injured sailors were evacuated Sunday
afternoon to the Brooke Army Burn Center in San Antonio, Texas. He
said they were in serious condition but did not elaborate.
   All the fatalities occurred inside the taxi van, which was
operated by the base's retail exchange. It was more heavily damaged
by fire than the car, Hines said.
   Long said the dead included five Navy personnel and the driver
of the van, a civilian employee at the base. He said the fourth
person injured, the driver of the private car, was in stable
condition at the base hospital.
   A base security vehicle observed the private vehicle speeding
about 1{ miles before it crashed into the van at 8:35 p.m. on
Sherman Avenue, the main road on the base, according to Long. The
security vehicle followed the private vehicle but could go no
faster than 40 mph, he said.
   ``The vehicle outran the naval station vehicle,'' but the
accident was not a result of ``hot pursuit,'' he said. ``The
security vehicle did not see the accident occur.''
   Long said the speed limit on the base is 25 mph.
   About 7,000 people, including military personnel and civilian
workers, live on the base at the eastern tip of communist Cuba. The
facility, which is enclosed and surrounded by a minefield, serves
as the main training site for the Atlantic Fleet.
</TEXT>
