<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NicaraguaMayDay     05-01 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua May Day,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Warns Of Military Operation If Peace Talks Fail.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega told a May Day
rally Sunday that his troops would launch their largest military
offensive ever if rebels do not agree to extend a cease-fire into a
permanent truce.
   On Saturday, government and rebel leaders ended three days of
talks in Managua without making significant progress. The
Sandinistas and rebels, known as Contras, agreed only to meet again
but they didn't set a date or place.
   ``Contras Uncompromising,'' a banner headline in the Sandinista
newspaper Barricada said Sunday. The story said the latest
negotiations ended ``without a single concrete result.''
   Defense Minister Gen. Humberto Ortega, the head of the
government's delegation and brother of the president, had said
Saturday there was some progress. He also said the negotiators had
agreed to meet again on May 12 at a still to be decided place.
   But that was disputed by Aristides Sanchez, a Contra spokesman.
He told reporters Saturday no date had been set for the next round
and the rebel negotiators would not return to Managua.
   The Contras had inisted the political talks be held in the
capital, and that was resisted for months by the Sandinistas.
   But Sanchez said, ``We won't return to Managua while there is a
climate of tension. There is not a favorable environment to talk in
Managua.''
   President Ortega said Sunday that future talks had to be in
Nicaragua but he did not specify Managua.
   The discussions are to define details of the March 23 cease-fire
pact signed after three days of negotiations at the southern border
post at Sapoa. It established a 60-day cease fire that took effect
April 1.
   But hopes of ending the six years of fighting have dimmed as
negotiators have been unable to agree on implementing the March
accords.
   On Friday the Contras turned down a Sandinista request to extend
the cease-fire another 30 days after May 30.
   The president told thousands of people at the rally to maintain
their guard.
   ``We have to be prepared because on May 30 if we haven't arrived
at an agreement, we are going to launch a large _ the largest
military offensive against the mercenary forces,'' he said.
   No major battle actions have been reported since the cease-fire
began.
   Opposition political parties and unions staged two peaceful May
Day marches in Managua.
   In one demonstration some marchers carried signs saying,
``Against Government Repression!'' and ``We Want Work, Not Military
Service!''
   Meanwhile, more than 30 construction workers and car mechanics
were in the seventh day of a hunger strike at a union hall. Police
were stationed outside the buidling and said it was ``prohibited
for passersby or working news media representatives to get close to
the building.''
   Police have detained about 40 people since last Monday for
protesting at the hall, headquarters of the General Workers
Federation. The federation is a coalition of socialist
anti-government unions.
   About 1,500 construction workers and auto mechanics walked off
their jobs at the end of February to demand higher wages.
</TEXT>
