<1ST_LINE>u i AM-BRF--BBC-Disease 1stLd-Writethru a0699 05-01 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--BBC-Disease, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBC Confirms Two Employee Cases of Legionnaires' Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with two cases confirmed, three suspected. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doorman and a workman contracted Legionnaires'
disease after working in British Broadcasting Corp. buildings, and
three more cases were suspected, the BBC said Sunday.
   Air conditioning systems in the main Broadcasting House in
central London and the BBC's nearby Duchess Street building were
cleaned, along with any other possible sources of infection, BBC
said.
   ``On the advice of the Public Health Laboratory Service,'' the
BBC said in a broadast Sunday, ``potential sources of Legionnaires'
disease are being disinfected.''
   The company checked the buildings after the two men developed
symptoms of the disease. They were sent to hospitals for testing
and their cases were confirmed, the company said.
   The suspected cases affect two BBC staff and one other person
who had been in the vicinity, the BBC said. No further information
about the victims was available.
   Legionnaires' disease produces symptoms similar to pneumonia and
is often caused by bacteria from water-cooled air conditioning
units.
   The illness was first diagnosed in July 1976 after 221 people
contracted it in Philadelphia at a convention of the Pennsylvania
American Legion. Thirty-four of the victims died.
   Doctors in the United States say Legionnaires' disease has
proved fatal in about 15 percent of cases.
   The BBC on Sunday broadcast an appeal for information ``on
anyone who has pneumonia or suspected Legionnaires' disease and who
has been in this area within the last two weeks.''
</TEXT>
