<HEAD>Rebel Sympathizers Throw Dynamite At Banks During May Day
Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators linked to the Shining Path
guerrilla movement threw sticks of dynamite at two banks and other
buildings during a May Day march through the capital Sunday.
   About 100 marchers belonging to a radical labor group linked to
the Maoist guerrillas marched on a main avenue shouting
anti-government slogans. Protesters hurled dynamite at two banks,
an insurance company's offices and a sporting goods shop, police
said.
   Seven sticks of the dynamite exploded, shattering windows of
several buildings and chipping walls. No one was reported hurt.
   Police said they deactivated two small bombs left by the
demonstrators.
   The marchers plastered doors and lamp posts with dozens of red
posters carrying the communist symbol of the hammer and sickle. The
posters commemorated May Day and urged workers to join the ``armed
struggle''against the government.
   Police converged on the area when the dynamite exploded and the
marchers scattered, witnesses said.
   Since last year the Shining Path has been working to infiltrate
and control unions, a new step in the group's efforts to undercut
the elected governement, according to counterinsurgency officials.
   More than 10,000 people, mainly highland peasenats have been
killed since Shining Path launched its insurgency in May 1980.
