<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 2242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Demjanjuk-Dov     05-01 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk-Dov,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Judge Discusses War Crimes Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli judge who presided over
the conviction of John Demjanjuk of war crimes said Sunday that the
public trial would help prevent a repetition of the Nazi Holocaust.
   The decision to prosecute Demjanjuk, a former Ohio autoworker,
was particularly important in light of recent criticism of Israel's
treatment of Palestinians in Israeli-occupied territory, said
Israeli Supreme Court Justice Dov Levin.
   ``When a pure and enlightened movement like Zionism is equated
with rascism, (the holocaust) could happen again,'' he said.
   The trial, in which Demjanjuk was accused by survivors of being
a death camp guard called Ivan the Terrible, reawakened memories of
Adolf Hitler's program to exterminate Jews and will help insure the
tragedy does not happen again, Dov said at the Fourth Annual Israel
Symposium at Beth El Temple here.
   Levin, 62, presided over a three-judge panel that sentenced
Demjanjuk to death last week. The only other person executed in
Israel's 40-year history was Adolf Eichmann, who directed the
extermination program. He was tried and hanged in 1962.
   Levin said he was convinced of Demjanjuk's guilt.
   Survivors of the Treblinka concentration camp in occupied Poland
remembered every moment of their meetings with Demjanjuk, he said.
They testified that he went beyond his duty, whipping and slashing
terrified prisoners on their way to the gas chambers.
   ``They dream about it,'' he said. ``That is why we were
convinced they remember everything.''
   Demjanjuk's attorneys argued their client, a Ukrainian Orthodox
Christian, was the victim of mistaken identity.
   Levin also said he was satisfied Demjanjuk received a fair
hearing at his 14-month trial. ``We are professional judges,'' he
said.
   Some Israelis expressed concern that the emotional courtroom
scene, in which many observers cheered and chanted for death after
his sentencing, lent credence to defense claims that Demjanjuk
could not receive a fair trial in Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880501-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-88 2242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     05-01 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY City Ballet Never Looked Like This Before</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York City Ballet entered the second week
of its three-week American Music Festival on Sunday with the odd,
nightmarish ``Archetypes,'' with ballerinas in clown masks and men
dressed as admirals.
   In Part 1, the ballerinas in masks take Heather Watts from her
partner, Jock Soto, and when he sees her again she has become like
all of them. He runs. In Part 2, men in three-piece suits with
briefcases are vaguely menaced by men in leotards and ski masks.
   Part 3 starts amusingly as Miss Watts' black coat is whisked
into the air, leaving her in underwear. She dances a long, sensual
duet with Soto, in admiral's uniform and gray hair. He tosses away
his elderly wig but instead of a happy ending, other admirals carry
him away and her coat flies back and she leaves. Part 4 started
fast and passionate and ended with what looked like a gang fight.
   Dancers looked as though they needed more rehearsal.
   Paul Schwartz composed the music on commission from the New York
City Ballet. Choreographer Robert Weiss, formerly of the New York
City Ballet, wrote a program note saying his ballet was inspired by
paintings by Jonathan Borofsky.
   The second ballet of the evening was Jerome Robbins' wonderful,
amusing ``Fancy Free'' to music by Leonard Bernstein from 1944.
   The evening in the New York State Theater ended with Lars
Lubovitch's ``Rhapsody in Blue'' to the famous Gershwin music,
which was danced on the festival's opening night.
   The principal male part looks as though it was choreographed for
rangy Christopher d'Amboise, who isn't with the company any more.
   The movement is the kind of free, wide-kicking, fast-spinning,
high-lifting dancing that says America, from cheerleaders to
barndancers. It's the energetic movement of a big country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
