<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Contras     05-01 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Return after Talks Stall, Want Next Round Held Outside
Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua May Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders returned from a second round of
stalled peace talks Sunday blaming Sandinista government for
reneging on promises and creating an oppressive atmosphere that
jeopardizes future talks in Nicaragua.
   ``It's obvious the Sandinistas have gone backward on their
promises and don't have any intention of fulfilling the agreement
we signed in Sapoa,'' said Contra leader Adolfo Calero after
returning here from Managua.
   Calero said he hoped the next round of talks tentatively planned
for May 12-14 will be held in Guatemala, the Dominican Republic or
Costa Rica because of Sandinista restrictions on personal freedoms
inside Nicaragua.
   ``They have been carrying on a succession of repressive actions
against the people of Nicaragua,'' Calero said.
   Sandinista police on Friday cordoned off the entrance to an
anti-government workers union where about 1,500 construction
workers were protesting economic measures enacted a week earlier.
   Also Friday, Jose Castillo Osejo, director of the
anti-Sandinista Radio Corporation, claimed Interior Minister Tomas
Borge summoned him to his office, berated Radio's reporting of the
demonstrations and punched him in the mouth.
   Calero also said Contra negotiators were forced to stay in their
hotel ``like it's a prison.''
   Calero and Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, two of the five-member
Nicaraguan Resistance directorate who met with reporters here,
denied a government announcement in Managua Saturday that some
rebel leaders were staying to continue talks.
   ``We all got on the bus at the airport and left, you could have
taken a group picture,'' Chamorro said. ``There's no need for
anybody to stay. We'll be back.''
   The talks are hung up on the workings of the cease-fire
agreement signed in Sapoa, Nicaragua, March 23. The pact calls for
Contra forces to enter truce zones, after which the government is
to free 700 political prisoners and allow Contras to join talks
with Nicaraguan political parties.
   During the truce, Contra forces may receive humanitarian
supplies. But rebel leaders say the latest round of talks stalled
over how that food, clothing and medicine would be delivered.
   The Contras Friday rejected a Sandinista proposal that the
International Committee of the Red Cross re-supply the rebels.
   Chamorro said Red Cross in Nicaragua is ``just another arm of
the Sandinista government.'' He preferred that a private carrier
agreeable to both sides bring in the goods.
   The rebels also turned down a government proposal to extend by a
month the 60-day cease-fire that began April 1, saying the offer
showed a lack of good will to fulfill the Sapoa agreement.
</TEXT>
