<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searching for new ways to cut federal
spending, Congress may finally be ready to butcher one of its most
sacred cows _ outdated and unneeded military bases.
   ``We no longer need to guard the Pony Express routes to the Wild
West. We no longer need to maintain moated forts to guard against
assault by British sailing ships,'' said Sen. William Roth, R-Del.
   ``We all know why these unnecessary bases have been kept open,''
Roth said. ``They have been maintained for selfish political
reasons in order to maintain a flow of defense dollars into our
states. But the budgetary good times are gone. We simply cannot
justify throwing money away.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate in Washington over a bill requiring a
company to give 60 days' notice before closing a plant puzzles
people in Europe, where such measures are woven into the fiber of
national welfare systems.
   ``I can't remember the subject being discussed in the 10 years
I've been working here,'' said Keith Faulkner, spokesman for the
Trades Union Congress, the umbrella movement of British organized
labor.
   ``I don't see what's the big deal,'' remarked French economist
Bernard Ewenczyk, a specialist in company bankruptcy law. ``It's
not an issue here.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush says there ``isn't a short list,
there isn't a long list'' yet of possible running mates, but he
indicates with some understatement that he wants to use less frenzy
in the selection than Ronald Reagan did eight years ago.
   ``I hope I'll make as good a choice but I'll use a different
method,'' says the vice president, who clinched enough delegates
last week to put a lock on the Republican presidential nomination.
   Bush was an 11th hour compromise at the 1980 convention after a
chaotic few days during which Reagan toyed with the idea of sharing
the ticket with former President Gerald Ford.
</TEXT>
