<TEXT>
   An American who is the only rabbi for East
Germany's tiny Jewish community said Sunday he's leaving the
communist country because of intolerable working conditions caused
by attempts to silence him.
   Isaac Neuman, a Polish-born survivor of Auschwitz and nine other
Nazi concentration camps, said he will depart for good by year's
end.
   In an interview at his East Berlin apartment, the controversial
65-year-old rabbi talked of interference from Jewish leadership and
objected to government treatment of his religious community.
``There regularly are informers at every worship service and at
every class,'' he said.
