<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CIA-ChineseEconomy 1stLd-Writethru f0003 05-01 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CIA-Chinese Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0003,0604</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Free-Market Trend Slowing In China</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf, In 1988, to make all verbs agree; SUBS 7th
graf, `Crucial, but,' to fix wording.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's march to a freer market economy is
slowing, and its reform-minded leaders are at odds over how much
further to go, the Central Intelligence Agency said in a report
released Sunday.
   ``One assessment of the current state of reforms is that China
now risks stalling out halfway on the road to a market economy,''
the CIA said in a report to Congress that was released by the Joint
Economic Committee.
   ``Although all Chinese leaders now consider themselves
reformers, a consensus over the ultimate shape of a reformed China
is notably lacking,'' the CIA said.
   The report, which examined all sections of the Chinese economy,
said it turned in a mixed performance last year.
   ``Chinese statistics indicate a substantial decline in the trade
deficit, high industrial growth and improved labor productivity,''
the report said. But it added that those favorable developments
were countered by increased inflation, slow growth in real income
in Chinese cities, disappointing grain production increases and
higher state subsidies to manufacturing enterprises, trading
corporations and big city consumers.
   In 1988, the CIA said, Peking is stressing efforts to reduce
inflation, increase profits of its enterprises and increase grain
output.
   ``Crucial but politically sensitive price reforms will proceed
slowly in order to minimize economic dislocations among
consumers,'' it said.
   The report said China's real gross national product rose by 9.4
percent in 1987, up from a 7.8 percent increase in 1986 but below
double-digit growth rates in 1984 and 1985.
   Chinese exports to the United States rose by a third in 1987,
reflecting the success of an export-push policy.
   But while U.S. sales to China rose by 12 percent _ recovering
from a slump in 1986 _ they remained below 1985 records.
   The result was that the U.S. trade deficit with China widened to
$3.4 billion, 60 percent higher than in 1986, the CIA said.
   Turning to defense, the CIA estimated that China spent about $12
billion on its military forces in 1986, about twice what the
Chinese government publicly reported.
   But it said that figure represents an overall declining trend in
military spending both as a share of the overall Chinese budget as
well as a share of China's gross national income.
   ``CIA estimates indicated that defense expenditures accounted
for about one third of China's total budget in 1978, and only
one-fifth of the budget in 1987,'' the report said.
   ``Moreover, we estimate that China's defense spending dropped
from 12 percent of gross national income in 1978 to only 5 percent
in 1987.
   That compares to 7 percent for the United States last year and
an estimated 20 percent to 25 percent for the Soviet Union.
   ``China has cut military spending by slashing personnel costs
and postponing the procurement of most major weapons,'' the CIA
said.
   It reported cuts of more than 3 million men since 1977.
   Overall, it said that China's military operating budget has
declined by about a fifth over the last eight years.
   Chinese purchases of weapons declined by about 10 percent
between 1978 and 1986, the agency said, because of decisions to
postpone major purchases until more technologically advanced
weapons systems become available.
   But it said spending on research, development and testing have
increased by about 25 percent over the last decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880501-0082 </DOCNO>
