<HEAD>Dart Group Fourth Qtr. Profit Down; Posts $19.7 Million Annual
Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. posted a sharply lower
profit in its fourth fiscal quarter, and said the stock market
crash was the main factor in its annual loss of $19.7 million.
   Dart, the retailing company that serves as a takeover vehicle
for its controlling Haft family, reported a profit of $1.4 million,
or 74 cents a share, in the three months ended Jan. 31. That
compared with a profit of $11.4 million, or $6.05 per share, in the
same period a year earlier.
   Fourth quarter revenue rose to $122.5 million from $108.9
million, Dart disclosed Friday.
   For the full fiscal year, Dart posted a loss of $19.7 million,
compared with a profit of $30.7 million, or $16.43 per share, in
the previous year. Annual revenue rose to $406.8 million from
$367.4 million.
   The annual loss stemmed mainly from the $67.1 million loss the
company suffered in its aborted attempted takeover of Dayton Hudson
Corp. After accumulating stock in the Minneapolis-based retailer,
the Hafts were forced to sell the shares at a loss during the
October stock market crash.
   Dart controls operations of the Crown Books and Trak Auto retail
chains.
</TEXT>
